w.awitawards.com.ph/nominees.html |date=January 29, 2010 }}\". Retrieved February 18, 2010</ref>\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" | PMPC Star Awards for Music\n| R&B Album of the Year\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| ''Soul in Love''\n| {{nom}}\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| <ref name=1pmpc>{{cite web|url=http://www.pep.ph/guide/music/4883/1st-star-awards-for-music-to-be-held-at-the-skydome-sm-north|title=1st Star Awards for Music to be held at the Skydome, SM North|publisher=pep.ph|date=October 13, 2009|accessdate=April 30, 2011}}</ref>\n|-\n| R&B Artist of the Year\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| Jay R (himself)\n| {{nom}}\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| <ref name=1pmpc/>\n|-\n| RX 93.1\n| OPM Song of the Year\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| \"Back in Time\"<br /><small>(Kyla and Jay R)</small>\n| {{won}}\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| <ref name=rx09>\"[http://www.stir.ph/LM/articles~level2/id-1264383625604_1/ai-null/article.html RX 93.1 Year End Countdown winners]\". ''stir.ph''retrieved January 31, 2010</ref>\n|-\n| rowspan=\"4\" | [[Wave 89.1|Wave 89.1 Urban Music Awards]]\n| Best Male Soul/R&B Artist\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| Jay R (himself)\n| {{nom}}\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| <ref name=wavenom>\"[http://www.wave891.fm/urbanmusicawards.html List of current Urban Music Awards Wave 89.1 nominees] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091119094839/http://www.wave891.fm/urbanmusicawards.html |date=2009-11-19 }}\". ''wave891.fm'' Retrieved January 31, 2010</ref>\n|-\n| Best Remake\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| \"Tattooed on My Mind\"<br /><small>(with [[D'Sound]])</small>\n| {{nom}}\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| <ref name=wavenom/>\n|-\n| Best Collaboration\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| \"Back in Time\"<br /><small>(Kyla and Jay R)</small>\n| {{won}}\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| <ref name=wave09>\"[http://www.stir.ph/LM/articles~level2/id-1264729896294_4/ai-null/Jay_Durias_Amber_Marcus_Davis_win_big_in_Urban_Music_Awards.html Big winners of the 1st Urban Music Awards]\". ''stir.ph''retrieved January 31, 2010</ref>\n|-\n| Male Style Icon Award\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| Jay R (himself)\n| {{nom}}\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| <ref name=wavenom/>\n|-\n| rowspan=\"5\" | 2010\n| rowspan=\"2\" | [[Myx Music Awards 2010|Myx Music Awards]]\n| Favorite Song\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" rowspan=\"2\"| \"Back in Time\"<br /><small>(Kyla and Jay R)</small>\n| {{won}}\n|\n|-\n| Favorite Collaboration\n| {{nom}}\n|\n|-\n| PMPC Star Awards for Music\n| R&B Artist of the Year\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" rowspan=\"3\"| Jay R (himself)\n| {{won}}\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| <ref name=star2010>{{cite web |url=http://www.pep.ph/news/27036/Sarah-Geronimo,-Christian-Bautista-and-Erik-Santos-win-top-honors-at-the-2nd-Star-Awards-for-Music/2/2 |title=Sarah Geronimo, Christian Bautista and Erik Santos win top honors at the 2nd Star Awards for Music |publisher=Philippine Entertainment Portal |date=October 11, 2010 |author=William Reyes |accessdate=November 3, 2010}}</ref>\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" | Wave 89.1 Urban Music Awards\n| Best Male Soul/R&B Artist\n| {{nom}}\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| <ref name=wave11>{{cite web|url=http://www.iamgab.me/entertainment/wave-89-9-2nd-urban-music-awards/ |title=Wave 89.9 2nd Urban Music Awards |publisher=iamgab.me |accessdate=April 22, 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110408013621/http://www.iamgab.me/entertainment/wave-89-9-2nd-urban-music-awards/ |archivedate=April 8, 2011 }}</ref>\n|-\n| Male Style Icon Award\n| {{nom}}\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| <ref name=wave11/>\n|-\n| rowspan=\"3\" | 2011\n| rowspan=\"2\" | Awit Awards\n| Best Collaboration\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| \"Muli\"<br /><small>(Jay R and [[Nina Girado|Nina]])</small>\n| {{nom}}\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| <ref name=awit11>\"[http://www.awitawards.com.ph/winners.html Awit Awards 2011 current winners list] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120331091814/http://www.awitawards.com.ph/winners.html |date=2012-03-31 }}\" retrieved July 24, 2011.</ref>\n|-\n| Album of the Year\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| ''[[Jay R Sings OPM Love Classics]]''\n| {{nom}}\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| <ref name=awit11/>\n|-\n| [[Myx Music Awards 2011|Myx Music Awards]]\n| Favorite Remake\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| \"Himala\"\n| {{nom}}\n|\n|}\n\n== See also ==\n* [[ALV Talent Circuit]]\n* [[Party Pilipinas]]\n* [[Kyla]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20100420103957/http://www.jayrsmusic.com/ Official website]\n* {{Allmusic | class = artist | id = mn0000462619 | label = Jay R }}\n* {{IMDb name|1830146|Jay R}}\n\n{{Jay R}}\n{{Prot\u00e9g\u00e9 (Philippine TV series)}}\n{{I Love OPM}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:1981 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American expatriates in the Philippines]]\n[[Category:American musicians of Filipino descent]]\n[[Category:Filipino male television actors]]\n[[Category:Filipino pop singers]]\n[[Category:Filipino male singers]]\n[[Category:Filipino songwriters]]\n[[Category:Filipino singer-songwriters]]\n[[Category:Filipino male voice actors]]\n[[Category:Filipino male models]]\n[[Category:GMA Network personalities]]\n[[Category:Male actors from Glendale, California]]\n[[Category:Writers from Glendale, California]]\n[[Category:ABS-CBN personalities]]\n[[Category:American contemporary R&B singers]]\n[[Category:American soul singers]]\n[[Category:21st-century American singers]]\n[[Category:21st-century Filipino singers]]\n[[Category:21st-century male singers]]\n[[Category:Filipino male film actors]]\n", "name_user": "Lenatagum", "label": "safe", "comment": "Asia's King of R&B", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jay_R"}
{"title_page": "National Socialist black metal", "text_new": "{{Infobox music genre\n| name              = National Socialist black metal\n| bgcolor           = #BB0022\n| color             = white\n| stylistic_origins = * [[Black metal]]\n* [[pagan metal]]\n* [[Rock Against Communism]]\n* [[Nazi punk|hatecore]]\n| cultural_origins  = Early 1990s to present, [[Europe]]\n| instruments       = * [[Singing|Vocals]]\n* [[electric guitar]]\n* [[bass guitar]]\n* [[Drum kit|drums]]\n| popularity        = Underground\n| other_topics      = *[[White power skinhead]]\n}}\n{{Nazism sidebar}}\n\n'''National Socialist black metal''', also known as '''NSBM''', '''Aryan black metal''' or '''Neo-Nazi black metal''', is a political movement within [[black metal]] music that promotes [[neo-Nazism]] and similar ideologies. NSBM artists typically combine neo-Nazi imagery and ideology with [[Paganism#Historical paganism|ethnic European paganism]], [[Satanism]], or [[Nazism and occultism|Nazi occultism]], and vehemently oppose [[Christianity]], [[Islam]] and [[Judaism]]. NSBM is not seen as a distinct genre, but as a [[neo-v\u00f6lkisch movements|neo-v\u00f6lkisch movement]] within black metal. According to [[Mattias Gardell]], NSBM musicians see this ideology as \"a logical extension of the political and spiritual dissidence inherent in black metal\".<ref name=\"Gardell\">Mattias Gardell, [[Gods of the Blood|''Gods of the Blood'' (2003)]], p.307</ref>\n\nAlthough there is an undercurrent of ethnic nationalism in black metal,{{sfn|Moynihan|S\u00f8derlind|2003|p=349-355}}<ref name=\"Gardell\"/><ref>{{cite journal |ref=harv |last1=Trafford |first1=Simon |last2=Pluskowski |first2=Aleks |editor-last=Marshall |editor-first=David W. |year=2007 |title=Antichrist Superstars: The Vikings in Hard Rock and Heavy Metal |url=https://www.academia.edu/521897/Antichrist_Superstars_The_Vikings_in_hard_rock_and_heavy_metal |journal=Mass Market Medieval: Essays on the Middle Ages in Popular Culture |publisher=[[McFarland & Company]] |pages=64 |isbn=978-0-7864-2922-6 }}</ref> NSBM artists are a small minority within the genre.<ref name=\"Gardell\"/>{{sfn|Olson|2008|p=123f}} NSBM artists are not always explicit with their political beliefs in the music, instead expressing their beliefs offstage.<ref name=reichsrock>{{cite book|last1=Dyck|first1=Kirsten|title=Reichsrock: The International Web of White-Power and Neo-Nazi Hate Music|date=2016|publisher=[[Rutgers University Press]]|location=New Brunswick|isbn=9780813574738|pages=58\u201361|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=sREVDQAAQBAJ&source=gbs_navlinks_s|accessdate=January 9, 2017}}</ref> Artists who hold [[Far-right politics|far-right]] or [[White nationalism|white nationalist]] beliefs but do not express these in their music are not often deemed NSBM by the greater black metal scene, but may be labelled as such by outside analysts.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bifff-berlin.de/aktuell72.html |title=Rechtes Neuheiden-Festival mit Nazi-Runen im \"SO 36\" |publisher=BIFFF ...|language=de}}</ref> Some black metal bands have also made references to [[Nazi Germany]] purely for [[shock value]], much like some [[punk rock]] and [[heavy metal music|heavy metal]] bands. While some black-metallers boycott NSBM artists, many are indifferent or appreciate the music without supporting the musicians.{{sfn|Olson|2008|p=99}} According to Christian Dornbusch and Hans-Peter Killguss's 2005 book ''Unheilige Allianzen'', v\u00f6lkisch [[pagan metal]] and neo-Nazism were the current trends in black metal, and in turn were affecting the broader metal scene.<ref>''Unheilige Allianzen'', p. 290. {{ISBN|3-89771-817-0}}</ref>\n\nThe emergence of NSBM coincided with the rise of the [[early Norwegian black metal scene]] in the early 1990s, particularly through the band [[Burzum]], whose sole member, [[Varg Vikernes]], developed his [[Satanism|Satanist]] beliefs and antagonism to Christianity into an increasingly white nationalist and neo-Nazi form of [[Heathenry (new religious movement)|Heathenry]]. The German band [[Absurd (band)|Absurd]] further developed the burgeoning scene with explicitly neo-Nazi lyrics and artistic themes.  The movement became especially popular in Eastern Europe, where it was developed by bands such as the Polish groups [[Graveland]] and [[Infernum]] and the Ukrainian band [[Hate Forest]]. The United States bands [[Grand Belial's Key]] and [[Judas Iscariot (band)|Judas Iscariot]] also became involved in the by-now international NSBM movement. As the movement grew internationally, it started to overlap with existing white supremacist and neo-Nazi musical forms such as [[Rock Against Communism]], [[Nazi punk|hatecore]], and the far-fight faction of [[Oi!]]. The Canadian neo-Nazi record label [[Resistance Records]] started releasing NSBM recordings, and even purchased Vikernes' label Cymophane Records. The United States white supremacist [[William Luther Pierce]] and his political organization [[National Alliance (United States)|National Alliance]] also became interested in the movement, and assisted Absurd frontman Hendrik M\u00f6bus when he fled to the United States to avoid arrest in Germany. In the early 2000s, bands such the Ukrainian [[Drudkh]] and [[Kroda]] and the Russian \u041c8\u041b8\u0422\u0425 continued the scene's popularity in Eastern Europe. In 2012, the NSBM [[Asgardsrei festival]] was established in [[Moscow]], Russia, and then in 2014 relocated to [[Kiev]], Ukraine, where it is closely linked to the activities of the [[Ukrainian nationalism|Ukrainian nationalist]] network [[Azov Battalion]] and functions as an international hub for neo-Nazism and other far-right politics.\n\n==Black metal==\n{{Main|Black metal}}\nBlack metal is a style of [[extreme metal]] music. Common traits include [[Tempo#Beats per minute|fast tempos]], a [[Screaming (music)#Black metal|shrieking]] vocal style,<ref name=metalsucks>{{cite web | url=http://www.metalsucks.net/2012/11/08/vons-satanic-blood-black-black-black-black-no-1/ | title=Von's Satanic Blood: Black Black Black Black No. 1 | publisher=[[MetalSucks]] | date=8 November 2012 | accessdate=8 May 2013 | author=O'Hagar, Sammy}}</ref><ref name=allmusic>{{cite web |url={{Allmusic|class=album|id=inri-mw0000243175|pure_url=yes}} |title=((( I.N.R.I. > Overview ))) |author=Rivadavia, Eduardo |website=[[AllMusic]] |accessdate=2007-12-18}}</ref><ref name=Sputnikmusic>{{cite web|last=Freeman|first=Channing|title=Album Review - Darkthrone: A Blaze in the Northern Sky|url=https://www.sputnikmusic.com/review/54469/Darkthrone-A-Blaze-in-the-Northern-Sky/|website=[[Sputnikmusic]]|accessdate=22 January 2013|date=18 January 2013}}</ref> heavily distorted [[Electric guitar|guitars]] played with [[tremolo picking]], raw ([[Lo-fi music|lo-fi]]) recording, unconventional [[song structure]]s, and an emphasis on atmosphere. Artists often appear in [[corpse paint]] and adopt pseudonyms. During the 1980s, several [[thrash metal|thrash]] and [[death metal]] bands formed a prototype for black metal.<ref name=\"Stylus Magazine\">{{cite magazine |url=http://www.stylusmagazine.com/articles/weekly_article/into-the-void-stylus-magazines-beginners-guide-to-metal.htm |title=Into the void: Stylus Magazine's Beginner's Guide to Metal |last1=Lee |first1=Cosmo |last2=Voegtlin |first2=Stewart |magazine=[[Stylus Magazine]] |accessdate=17 May 2010}}</ref> Initially a synonym for \"Satanic metal,\"<ref>{{cite book |last=McIver |first=Joel |authorlink=Joel McIver |title=Justice for All - The Truth About Metallica |edition=updated |publisher=Omnibus Press |year=2009 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=SvW-uN-qEbIC&pg=PT98&dq=%22black+metal%22#v=onepage&q=%22black%20metal%22&f=false |accessdate=4 September 2012}}</ref> black metal is often met with hostility from mainstream culture, due to the actions and [[Black metal#Ideology|ideologies]] associated with it. Many artists express extreme [[Anti-Christian sentiment|anti-Christian]] and [[Misanthropy|misanthropic]] views, advocating various forms of [[Satanism]] or [[Polytheistic reconstructionism|ethnic paganism]]. In the 1990s, members of the scene were responsible for a spate of [[Black metal#Church burnings|church burnings]] and murders. There is also a small neo-Nazi movement within black metal, although it has been shunned by many prominent artists.<ref name=billzebub/><ref name=kingovhell>{{cite web |url=http://www.maelstrom.nu/ezine/interview_iss50_224.php |title=Interview with Jotunspor |last=\u0160kot |first=Mladen |work=maelstrom.nu |accessdate=4 September 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110927131014/http://www.maelstrom.nu/ezine/interview_iss50_224.php |archivedate=27 September 2011 }}</ref><ref name=infernus1>{{cite web |url=http://www.roadrunnerrecords.com/blabbermouth.Net/news.aspx?mode=Article&newsitemID=93004 |title=Blabbermouth.net - Gorgoroth Guitarist Infernus: 'I Personally Am Against Racism in Both Thought and Practice' |date=15 March 2008 |work=[[Blabbermouth.net]] |accessdate=4 September 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090422024415/http://www.roadrunnerrecords.com/blabbermouth.Net/news.aspx?mode=Article&newsitemID=93004 |archivedate=22 April 2009 }}</ref> Generally, black metal strives to remain [[Underground music|underground]], inaccessible to the mainstream.{{sfn|Olson|2008|p=30}}\n\n== History ==\n{{Listen\n|filename = \u041b\u044e\u0442\u044c \u043d\u0430\u0448\u043e\u0457 \u0432\u0456\u0442\u0447\u0438\u0437\u043d\u0438.ogg\n|title = \u00ab\u0406\u0434\u0443 \u043d\u0430 \u0432\u0438!\u00bb (2002)\n|description = \u00ab\u041b\u044e\u0442\u044c \u043d\u0430\u0448\u043e\u0457 \u0432\u0456\u0442\u0447\u0438\u0437\u043d\u0438\u00bb, demonstrating NSBM\n}}\nIn the 1980s, 'black metal' referred to heavy metal bands with Satanic lyrics and imagery. Black metal originated with the band [[Venom (band)|Venom]] out of [[Newcastle upon Tyne|Newcastle]], [[England]]. Their debut album ''[[Welcome to Hell|Welcome To Hell]]'' released in 1981 and was followed by 1982's ''[[Black metal|Black Metal]]''. Venom's image lyrics and musical style were copied and inspired by bands such as [[Slayer]], [[Hellhammer]], [[Celtic Frost]], [[Bathory (band)|Bathory]], [[Exodus (American band)|Exodus]], and [[Possessed (band)|Possessed]]. In the early 1990s, the [[early Norwegian black metal scene]] developed the style into a distinct genre. The scene members were fiercely [[Criticism of Christianity|anti-Christian]] and generally presented themselves as [[misanthropy|misanthropic]] [[Theistic Satanism|Devil-worshipers]] who wanted to spread hatred, sorrow and evil. However, some bands wrote about pre-Christian Scandinavia and its folklore. In 1992, members of the scene burnt down a number of churches. In August of the same year, [[Faust (musician)|Faust]] of [[Emperor (band)|Emperor]] killed a gay man who had propositioned him in [[Lillehammer]]. In August 1993, [[Varg Vikernes]] of [[Burzum]] killed fellow musician [[Euronymous]] \u2013 a well-known figure in the scene \u2013 and was arrested shortly after. Euronymous was said to be a [[communism|communist]], but Vikernes denies killing him over ideology. Although Vikernes's music was never explicitly political, he began to express neo-Nazi views in writings and interviews after his arrest.\n\nVikernes is generally seen as being responsible for popularizing such views in the black metal scene. According to an interview in ''Blood & Honour'' magazine, he contacted neo-Nazi organization Zorn 88 (later called the [[National Socialist Movement of Norway]]) in 1992<ref name=\"Unheiligepage277\">''Unheilige Allianzen'', p. 277.</ref> and joined White Aryan Resistance before he killed Euronymous.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.berlinonline.de/berliner-zeitung/archiv/.bin/dump.fcgi/1996/0902/reporter/0002/?subnav=Spezial|archive-url=https://archive.is/20120723205956/http://www.berlinonline.de/berliner-zeitung/archiv/.bin/dump.fcgi/1996/0902/reporter/0002/?subnav=Spezial|url-status=dead|archive-date=23 July 2012|title=Aktuell|website=www.berlinonline.de|accessdate=29 August 2017}}</ref> While in prison, \"Vikernes began to formulate his nationalist heathen ideology\"<ref>Goodrick-Clarke, p. 204.</ref> and wrote a manifesto called ''Vargsm\u00e5l''. It became available on the internet for a while in 1996,<ref>''Lords of Chaos'', p. 159.</ref> and in 1997 it was printed by a Norwegian publisher.{{citation needed|date=February 2017}}  By 2004, Vikernes abandoned playing metal music because of its origin as \"Negro music\", and argued that the 'metal heads' tend to behave like a bunch of 'White Niggers', so to speak, with their sex, drugs and rock'n'roll culture.\"<ref name=\":3\" />\n\nSome other members of the early Norwegian scene explored with Nazi themes and imagery, but this was partly an attempt to provoke listeners.{{sfn|Olson|2008|p=101}} Vikernes later claimed that the scene had begun \"as a nationalistic (Norwegian-centric), racist and anti-Christian revolt\" but was \"hijacked\" by the \"Jew-dominated music industry\". He claims the industry made it into another tool with which to destroy Europe, by promoting bands who embraced \"everything sick and anti-European on this planet, from porn and promiscuity to drugs and homosexuality\".<ref>Vikernes, Varg. [http://thuleanperspective.com/2013/03/07/how-to-revolt-in-practise-ii/ \"How to revolt in practise II] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130311135742/http://thuleanperspective.com/2013/03/07/how-to-revolt-in-practise-ii/ |date=2013-03-11 }}\". Thulean Perspective. 7 March 2013.</ref> Hendrik M\u00f6bus of [[Absurd (band)|Absurd]] called NSBM the \"logical conclusion\" of the Norwegian black metal movement and interpreted the church burnings as a \"cultural [[atavism]]\".<ref name=\"M\u00f6bus\"/>\n\nVikernes wrote some lyrics for the album ''[[Transilvanian Hunger]]'' by [[Darkthrone]], another key band in the Norwegian scene. It was released in 1994 with ''Norsk Arisk Black Metal'' ('Norwegian Aryan Black Metal') printed on the back cover. This caused much controversy, and Darkthrone claimed that they were \"not a Nazi band nor a political band\".<ref name=\"MusicMight biography\">{{cite web |url=http://www.musicmight.com/artist/norway/kolbotn/darkthrone |title=MusicMight :: Artists :: Darkthrone |work=[[MusicMight]] |accessdate=23 September 2012}}</ref> In a 2007 documentary, [[Fenriz]] claimed he was once arrested while participating in an anti-[[apartheid]] demonstration and later had a \"phase of being really angry with&nbsp;... other races\" before he became \"totally unengaged in [political] shit\".<ref name=\"billzebub2\">Zebub, Bill (2007). ''Black Metal: A Documentary''.</ref>\n\nAt around this time, some other Scandinavian black-metallers made racist statements and utilized Nazi paraphernalia. In 1994, [[Jan Axel Blomberg|Hellhammer]], the drummer for the Norwegian band [[Mayhem (band)|Mayhem]], said of the genre's links with racism: \"I'll put it this way, we don't like black people here. Black Metal is for white people\".<ref>''Lords of Chaos'', p. 351.</ref> When Mayhem re-formed after Euronymous's death, they began releasing merchandise bearing World War II-era [[Nazi symbolism|Nazi symbols]].<ref>[http://www.blabbermouth.net/news/mayhem-frontman-says-varg-vikernes-is-very-polite-and-kind/ Mayhem Frontman Says Varg Vikernes Is 'Very Polite And Kind']. [[Blabbermouth.net]]. 26 January 2010.</ref> However, in a later interview, Hellhammer said \"I don't give a crap if the fans are white, black, green, yellow, or blue. For me music and politics don't go hand in hand\".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://thydoom.com/en/interviews/6.html |title=ThyDoom.com |publisher=ThyDoom.com |accessdate=2011-10-06 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101002121928/http://thydoom.com/en/interviews/6.html |archivedate=2010-10-02 }}</ref> In 1995, prominent Norwegian black metal vocalist [[Gaahl]] described \"niggers\" and \"mulattoes\" as \"subhuman\" and stated his admiration for Vikernes and Adolf Hitler. However, he too has since distanced himself from these statements.<ref name=\"rockhardgaahl\">{{cite web |url=http://www.roadrunnerrecords.com/blabbermouth.net/news.aspx?mode=Article&newsitemID=107859 |title=BLABBERMOUTH.NET \u2013 GORGOROTH Frontman Opens Up About His Sexual Orientation: 'I've Never Made Any Secret About It' |publisher=Roadrunnerrecords.com |accessdate=2012-02-10 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111121222135/http://www.roadrunnerrecords.com/blabbermouth.net/news.aspx?mode=Article&newsitemID=107859 |archivedate=2011-11-21 }}</ref>  Gaahl was voted Gay Person of the Year in 2010 in Bergen.<ref name=\"Trelldom interview\">{{cite web|url=http://www.gorgoroth.com.pl/english/art-interview_with_gaahl_from_polish_holocaust_magazine_1995|archive-url=https://archive.is/20130416072609/http://www.gorgoroth.com.pl/english/art-interview_with_gaahl_from_polish_holocaust_magazine_1995|url-status=dead|archive-date=16 April 2013|title=Interview with Gaahl|accessdate=29 August 2017}}</ref> According to the authors of ''Lords of Chaos'', in 1995, three Swedish black-metallers (including Mika \"Belfagor\" Hakola of the band [[Nefandus]]) went on a \"niggerhunt\" in [[Link\u00f6ping]]. Wielding an axe and two machetes, they \"terrorized\" a black man.<ref>''Lords of Chaos'', pp. 308\u2013309.</ref> Nefandus were later \"considered to be Nazi sympathizers\", though Belfagor explained: \"This could not be further from the truth, but I guess this has to do with some of the controversial comments I made in various magazines in my youth, when I still aspired to play in the most hated band in the world. I used a lot of provocative language back then. But to sort things out: I associate with people of all creeds and colours. ... So to be labeled a Nazi or a racist is very offensive to me\".<ref>Terry Demeter: ''Ofermod''. ''Breath of the Dragon''. In: ''Unrestrained Magazine'', no. 39, p. 74.</ref>\n\nOne of the first explicitly NSBM releases was the 1995 demo ''Thuringian Pagan Madness'' by German band [[Absurd (band)|Absurd]]. It was recorded while the members were imprisoned for murdering a boy from their school. On the demo cover is a photograph of his gravestone and pro-Nazi statements.<ref>[[Nicholas Goodrick-Clarke]]: ''Black Sun: Aryan Cults, Esoteric Nazism, and the Politics of Identity''. NYU Press, 2003. p. 206.</ref> Other bands deemed to be part of the early NSBM scene include [[Graveland]], and [[Infernum]] (from [[Poland]]),<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.decibelmagazine.com/2013/05/13/interview-author-dayal-patterson-on-black-metal-evolution-of-the-cult/|title=INTERVIEW: Author Dayal Patterson on Black Metal: Evolution of the Cult|last=Horsley|first=Jonathan|date=2013-05-13|website=[[Decibel (magazine)|Decibel]]|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref> Branikald (from [[Russia]]), and [[Spear of Longinus (band)|Spear of Longinus]] and [[Waffenbr\u00fcder]] (from [[Australia]]). Rob Darken of Graveland in particular was a very central figure in the development of NSBM in Poland.<ref name=\":1\" /> In the 1990s, some of the earliest American black metal bands\u2014like [[Grand Belial's Key]] and [[Judas Iscariot (band)|Judas Iscariot]]\u2014joined an international NSBM organization called the Pagan Front, although Judas Iscariot's sole member [[Andrew Harris (musician)|Akhenaten]] left the organization.<ref name=\"mh82007\">Gunnar Sauermann: ''Special: Black Metal in den USA''. ''Schwarzes Amerika''. In: ''[[Metal Hammer]] Germany'', August 2007, p. 88.</ref> Thelemnar, the drummer of German band [[Secrets of the Moon]], said he got to know him \"only as an intelligent person and never as a Nazi\".<ref name=\"mh82007\" />\n\nIn 2012, Alexey Levkin, frontman of the band \u041c8\u041b8\u0422\u0425, along with others, started the NSBM music festival [[Asgardsrei festival|Asgardsrei]] in [[Moscow]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://militant.zone/ar2017/|title=ASGARDSREI 2017 \u2013 Absurd, Peste Noire, Goatmoon, Naer Mataron, M8L8TH, Burshtyn (Kiev, 16.12.2017) {{!}} Militant Zone|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref><ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.bellingcat.com/news/2020/01/02/dispatches-from-asgardsrei-ukraines-annual-neo-nazi-music-festival/|title=Dispatches From Asgardsrei: Ukraine\u2019s Annual Neo-Nazi Music Festival|last=Colborne|first=Michael|date=2020-01-02|website=[[Bellingcat]]|language=en-GB|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref> The event is named after the 1999 album of the same name by Absurd.<ref name=\"newyorker\" /> The festival was relocated to [[Kiev]] in 2014 when Levkin and the other organizers relocated to [[Ukraine]] to join the [[Azov Battalion]].<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":2\">{{Cite news|last=Colborne|first=Michael|url=https://www.haaretz.com/world-news/europe/.premium-most-neo-nazi-music-festivals-are-closely-guarded-secrets-not-this-one-1.8260218|title=Most neo-Nazi Music Festivals Are Closely Guarded Secrets \u2014 Not This One in Ukraine|date=2019-12-12|work=[[Haaretz]]|access-date=2020-04-08|url-status=live|language=en}}</ref>\n\n== Ideology ==\nNSBM typically melds Neo-Nazi beliefs (such as [[fascism]], [[white supremacy]], [[white separatism]], [[white nationalism]], [[Far-right politics|right-wing extremism]], [[antisemitism]], [[xenophobia]], [[ethnic separatism]], with some [[National-anarchism|National-anarchist]] tendencies and admiration of [[Adolf Hitler]]) with hostility to \"foreign\" religions. Bands often promote ethnic European paganism, occultism, or Satanism. Hendrik M\u00f6bus of Absurd described Nazism as the \"most perfect (and only realistic!) synthesis of Satanic/[[Luciferianism|Luciferian]] [[will to power]], elitist [[Social Darwinism]], connected to Aryan [[Germanic paganism]]\".<ref>Stormblast, Nr. 2-3, 1999, citation taken from [http://www.akweb.de/ak_s/ak428/31.htm ak \u2013 analyse & kritik \u2013 zeitung f\u00fcr linke Debatte und Praxis / Nr. 428 / 8.7.1999]</ref> Members of the band Der St\u00fcrmer (named after the [[Der St\u00fcrmer|antisemitic newspaper]] edited by [[Julius Streicher]]) subscribe to [[Esoteric Nazism]], leaning on the works of [[Savitri Devi]] and [[Julius Evola]].<ref name=\"LEGEONES\">{{cite web|url=http://www.thepaganfront.com/dersturmer/interviews/LEGEONES.html|title=Der St\u00fcrmer interview published in LEGEONES magazine|publisher=|accessdate=29 August 2017}}</ref> Famine of [[Peste Noire]] stated in an interview that he prefers [[Italian Fascism]] instead of [[Nazism]] as an ideology.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.lamesnieherlequin.com/2014/07/translation-of-the-kpn-interview-for-cercle-non-conforme/,%20https://www.lamesnieherlequin.com/2014/07/translation-of-the-kpn-interview-for-cercle-non-conforme/|title=La Mesnie Herlequin \u00bb English translation of the PESTE NOIRE interview for Cercle Non Conforme|last=Cercle Non Conforme|first=|date=July 22, 2014|website=|others=Translated by M.D.L. and L\u2019Atrabilaire|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref>\n\n=== Anti-Christianity and antisemitism ===\nTypically NSBM musicians regard Christianity as a product of an alleged [[Jewish conspiracy]] to undermine the [[Aryan race]] by eliminating their ''Artglauben'' and their \"original\" culture.<ref name=\"akweb\">{{cite web|url=http://www.akweb.de/ak_s/ak428/31.htm|title=ak 428: Unheilige Allianz|website=www.akweb.de|accessdate=29 August 2017}}</ref> These musicians usually reject the legitimacy of [[Christianity and antisemitism|Christian antisemitism]] as well as the [[German Christians]] movement, which celebrated and promoted Nazi ideology in the context of an unorthodox [[Christian theology|Christian theological]] framework. Hjarulv Henker of the band Der St\u00fcrmer said:\n{{quote|I don't think that a dogma like Christianity has a place in Aryandom. There is no way to make Christianity fit into the Weltanschauung of the Aryan Overman. Christianity teaches humbleness, the loss of National and Racial identity, and equality, things alien to our cosmotheory. You cannot combine Jesus with characters who represent Aryan ethics. ... Christianity is Christianity and it is Jewish by its very birth and conception, a vehicle in the Jewish world domination and designed as such.<ref name=\"LEGEONES\"/>}}\n\n=== White supremacy ===\nNSBM musicians such as Varg Vikernes of Burzum and Famine of Peste Noire have expressed a white supremacist concern about \"[[Miscegenation|race mixing]]\" and preserving the purity of the [[white race]] and the traditional cultures of white European nations.<ref name=\":3\">{{cite web|url=http://www.burzum.org/eng/library/interview01.shtml|title=Interview with Varg Vikernes|last=BG|first=|date=August 12, 2004|website=www.burzum.org|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|accessdate=29 August 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.lamag.com/culturefiles/horna-finnish-metal/|title=UPDATE: DTLA Bar Cancels Far-Right Black Metal Band's Gig|last=Stuart|first=Gwynedd|date=2019-03-28|website=[[Los Angeles Magazine]]|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref><ref>Dyck, Kristin, 2017. pp. 59-60.</ref> Somewhat perplexingly, NSBM has been popular in Poland and other Slavic countries, despite the fact that, historically, German Nazis viewed Slavic people as subhuman racial inferiors and intended to eliminate them.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Patterson|first=Dayal|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=-kIxCgAAQBAJ|title=Black Metal: Evolution of the Cult|date=2013-11-25|publisher=Feral House|year=|isbn=978-1-936239-76-4|location=|pages=362|language=en}}</ref> This contradiction is either masked, relativized or excused as a historical mistake. A conspiracy theory says the Jews would have prevented an alliance between Nazi Germany and other Eastern European countries.<ref>Unheilige Allianzen, page 239</ref> [[Knjaz Varggoth]], singer and guitarist of the Ukrainian band [[Nokturnal Mortum]], gives the following explanation for the contradiction: \"Goruth of the Russian band Temnozor sees the Slavs and Germans as a part of a [[Hyperborea]]n Aryan race and nowadays differing due to its degeneration.\".<ref>Unheilige Allianzen, page 250</ref> The Polish band Graveland has contended that it considers its members [[Celts|Celtic]] or [[Aryan race|Aryan]] rather than Slavonic.\n\n=== Paganism ===\n{{see also|Viking metal}}\nAs part of their anti-Christianity, anti-semitism and the idea that White Europeans should return to their \"native\" ways, most NSBM bands promote ethnic European paganism. Hendrik M\u00f6bus interpreted the church burnings in Norway as:\n{{quote|[A] cultural atavism, a sudden and inexplicable plunge back into pre-Christian, medieval conditions in all but outward reality. Like the Swiss psychologist, Carl Gustav Jung, would have said: Ancient archetypes resurfaced from our collective unconscious and repossessed receptive minds \u2013 which were, as a rule, still developing and thus especially impressible. The thus affected teenagers found themselves with an archaic state of mind and like in a mass-hysteria, they induced their condition unto others. It goes without saying that a, say, 18 year old adolescent who suddenly felt out of tune with his environment lacked the insight for a self-analysis.<ref name=\"M\u00f6bus\">Hendrik M\u00f6bus: [https://web.archive.org/web/20060107011622/http://www.thepaganfront.com/pf.php?show=articles&article=1 ''National Socialist Black Metal''], mirrored on ''[[Internet Archive|Archive.org]]''.</ref>}} He argues that later on they would have realized the meaning of these emotions, begun to identify with paganism and taken \"an active interest in Nationalist politics designed to preserve and to cultivate this very heritage\".<ref name=\"M\u00f6bus\"/>\n\nThe booklet of the Absurd album ''[[Asgardsrei]]'' depicts the [[Knights Templar]], the [[Teutonic Order]] and the [[Waffen-SS]] as warriors of the \"Asgardsrei\", which the bands define as a term for an alleged godly and Germanic group of warriors.\n\n=== Satanism ===\nBesides pagan beliefs, part of the NSBM scene embraces an interpretation of [[Theistic Satanism]], depicting [[Satan]] as an ancient Aryan counterpart to [[Yahweh]], the god of the Jews and Christians. This view is often called \"[[Neo-v\u00f6lkisch movements|v\u00f6lkisch]] Satanism\"<ref>Wintry Night Nonstop/Aenaon Skotos Anosion, published around 2000: Frost/Sadorass [Interview with Sadorass]. Citation taken from Unheilige Allianzen, page 202</ref> or \"Aryan Satanism\". Chraesvelgoron of The True Frost sees Nazism as the political appearance of Satanism and the collective deification of man as a social animal, as godliness instead of humaneness.<ref>Szene-Almanach 1998, page 48</ref><ref>Strength through War, issue 4, Summer 2003, o.S.: Frost. Interview answered by Chraesvelgoron. Citation taken from Unheilige Allianzen, page 202</ref> His bandmate Sadorass calls the same ideology a development of blood and soil (v\u00f6lkisch way), diverse occult teachings and the ideas of [[Friedrich Nietzsche]] in connection to Darwin's evolution theories.<ref>Flagellation, No. 2, 2001, page 29. Citation taken from Unheilige Allianzen, page 203</ref> Greek black metal musician [[Magus Wampyr Daoloth]] (of [[Necromantia]] and [[Thou Art Lord]]) said in an interview for ''Lords of Chaos'': \"If you consider that fascism and Satanism have a lot of similarities as they both advocate power, spiritual and physical excellence, responsibility, survival of the fittest, elitism, etc., it's logical that some bands advocate both\".<ref>''Lords of Chaos'', p. 308.</ref>\n\nHowever, many pagan and [[Far-right politics|far-right]] bands see Satanism as a part of Christianity or Judaism.<ref>Gammadion, No. 1, 1997, o.S.: Capricornus. Citation taken from Unheilige Allianzen, page 241</ref> Also, some non-political Satanic black metal musicians hold pagan bands in contempt, and do not recognize them as black metal because their lyrics and ideology do not include Satanism.\n\n== Connections with broader white nationalist movements ==\nMany white nationalists have warmly received NSBM for its lyrical content and ideals. However, some have not, due to the music style as well as the genre's perceived association with the rock & roll lifestyle.<ref name=uh280>''Unheilige Allianzen'', p.280</ref> However, ''Lords of Chaos'' notes that alcohol and illegal drugs never played a big part in the Norwegian black metal scene.<ref>''Lords of Chaos'', p.327</ref> Some also reject black metal musicians and fans since many of them have long hair, which they associate with [[hippies]] and left-wingers, though some black metal musicians like [[Jon N\u00f6dtveidt]] did not follow this fashion and shaved their heads.<ref name=uh280/> Dayal Patterson writes that \"NSBM has become a movement in its own right,\" one which has reached [[Western Europe]] and the Americas and overlapped with fans of more traditional far-right music genres such as [[Oi!]] and [[Rock Against Communism]].<ref name=\":6\">Patterson, Dayal, 2013. p. 365</ref>\n\nThe record label [[Resistance Records]], a Canadian record label promoting white nationalism and white separatism, purchased Vikernes' Cymophane Records and began releasing black metal recordings, many through a sub-label, Unholy Records.<ref name=\":6\" /> [[William Luther Pierce]], founder of the white nationalist [[National Alliance (United States)|National Alliance]], sought to promote NSBM as well as other forms of white nationalist music through Resistance, believing that music would \"make the National Alliance rich and spread its message most effectively\".<ref name=\"pierce\">{{cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/obituaries/william-pierce-649470.html|title=US|publisher=|accessdate=29 August 2017}}</ref> To this end, he accommodated Absurd frontman Hendrik M\u00f6bus while the latter had fled to the United States to evade German authorities. Although Pierce appreciated the ideological mindset of NSBM and Resistance Records, as well as the financial gains, the music did not personally appeal to him, and he attacked the \"sex, drugs & rock'n'roll\" and what he called \"negroid\" influences.<ref name=\"pierce2\">{{cite web|url=http://www.decibelmagazine.com/features/may2006/nsbm.aspx|title=Decibel Magazine|accessdate=29 August 2017|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080208184453/http://www.decibelmagazine.com/features/may2006/nsbm.aspx|archivedate=8 February 2008}}</ref>\n\nAsgardsrei festival, which has established itself as the major festival for NSBM, has been noted by analysts and journalists to function as a meetup point and pan-European and transnational networking hub for neo-Nazis, white supremacists, and other far-right extremists.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":2\" /><ref name=\":5\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.vice.com/en_us/article/dygg9j/a-black-metal-festival-in-ukraine-this-weekend-is-the-neo-nazi-networking-event-of-the-year|title=A Black Metal Festival in Ukraine This Weekend Is the Neo-Nazi Networking Event of the Year|last=Hume|first=Tim|date=2019-12-13|website=[[Vice (magazine)|Vice]]|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref> In addition to the concert organizers' connections to the far-right [[Ukrainian nationalism|Ukrainian nationalist]] Azov Battalion, Ukrainian far-right political party [[National Corps]], and Russian-Ukrainian neo-Nazi movement Wotanjugend,<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":5\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bellingcat.com/news/uk-and-europe/2019/09/04/the-hardcore-russian-neo-nazi-group-that-calls-ukraine-home/|title=The \u201cHardcore\u201d Russian Neo-Nazi Group That Calls Ukraine Home|last=Colborne|first=Michael|last2=Kuzmenko|first2=Okesiy|date=2019-09-04|website=[[Bellingcat]]|language=en-GB|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref> members of the German neo-Nazi party [[The III. Path]], the United States-based [[Right-wing terrorism|neo-Nazi terrorist]] organization [[Atomwaffen Division]], the Italian [[Neo-fascism|neo-fascist]] movement and former political party [[CasaPound]], and the Greek neo-Nazi [[Metaxism|Metaxist]] party [[Golden Dawn (political party)|Golden Dawn]] have all participated in the festival.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":2\" /><ref name=\":5\" /> Members of neo-Nazi forums and chats such as Iron March, [[Stormfront (website)|Stormfront]], and neo-Nazi chat servers on [[Discord (software)|Discord]], have attended and praised Asgardsrei,<ref name=\":2\" /> and the American white nationalist [[Greg Johnson (white nationalist)|Greg Johnson]] posted a review of the 2019 festival on his [[alt-right]] publication Counter Currents.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n== Connections to black metal scene ==\nNSBM artists are a minority within black metal, according to Mattias Gardell.<ref name=\"Gardell\"/> They have also been rejected or strongly criticized by many prominent black metal musicians \u2013 including [[Jon N\u00f6dtveidt]],<ref name=\"Dissection\"/> [[Tormentor (musician)|Tormentor]],<ref name=\"Tormentor\"/> [[King ov Hell]],<ref name=\"kingovhell2\">{{cite web|url=http://www.maelstromzine.com/ezine/interview_iss50_224.php |title=Interview with JOTUNSPOR :: Maelstrom  :: Issue No 50|website=www.maelstromzine.com|accessdate=29 August 2017}}</ref> [[Infernus]],<ref name=\"infernus2\">{{cite web|url=http://www.roadrunnerrecords.com/page-not-found|title=Roadrunner Records Page Not Found|website=Roadrunner Records  Official Website|accessdate=29 August 2017}}</ref> [[Lord Ahriman]],<ref name=\"billzebub\">Zebub, Bill (2007). ''Black Metal: A Documentary''.</ref> [[Emperor Magus Caligula]],<ref name=\"billzebub\" /><ref name=\"caligulayoutube\">{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=d6pYjLyxCHo|title=YouTube|website=www.youtube.com|accessdate=29 August 2017}}</ref> [[Summoning (band)|Protector]],<ref name=\"Protector\">{{cite web|url=http://www.summoning.info/Stuff/PoliticalStatements.html|title=Political Statements from Protector (Summoning)|accessdate=29 August 2017|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120630125512/http://www.summoning.info/Stuff/PoliticalStatements.html|archivedate=30 June 2012}}</ref> Erik Danielsson of [[Watain]],<ref>Doomsdayzach: [http://www.globaldomination.se/interviews/watain-erik-danielsson ''Watain \u2013 Erik Danielsson (first one)''] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081024002551/http://www.globaldomination.se/interviews/watain-erik-danielsson |date=2008-10-24 }}, 24 July 2007, accessed on 31 March 2013.</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://exclaim.ca/music/article/watain_stand_for_black_metal_against_the_genres_nazi_flirtations|title=Watain Address Their Ideology Following Nazi Salute Controversy|last=Zorgdrager|first=Bradley|date=March 29, 2018|website=[[Exclaim!]]|language=en-ca|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-10}}</ref><ref>Ronald Ziegler: [https://web.archive.org/web/20030121034117/http://www.grimrune.com/watain/heint.html ''Merchandise whorery''], accessed on 31 March 2013.</ref> and the members of [[Arkhon Infaustus]].<ref name=\"billzebub\" />\n\nSome black-metallers liken Nazism to Christianity in that it is [[Authoritarianism|authoritarian]], [[Collectivism|collectivist]], and involves a \"[[herd mentality]]\".<ref name=\"Dissection\">{{cite web|url=http://www.metalcentre.com/webzine.php?p=interviews&lang=eng&nr=123|title=METAL CENTRE Webzine: News, Gallery, Reviews, Interviews etc. - 08/29/2017|first=ataman|last=Tolovy|website=www.metalcentre.com|accessdate=29 August 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"Tormentor\">Metal Heart 2/00</ref> It also conflicts with the [[Misanthropy|misanthropic]] views of many artists; Benjamin Hedge Olson writes that the shunning of Nazism within the scene \"has nothing to do with notions of a 'universal humanity' or a rejection of hate\" but that Nazism is shunned \"because its hatred is too specific and exclusive\".{{sfn|Olson|2008|p=123}} Joakim of [[Craft (metal band)|Craft]] said, \"I don't think national socialism mix[es] with the ideology of real Black Metal in a way, but that doesn't go further than labels. I only think NS Black Metal is an inappropriate label for the music\".<ref name=\"darkside\">Thomas Legros: [http://www.voicesfromthedarkside.de/Interviews/CRAFT--6878.html ''Craft''], accessed on 31 March 2013.</ref> While some black-metallers boycott NSBM bands and labels, others draw a line between the ''music'' and the ''musicians'', as they only care for the music. Some have criticized this as passive support for NSBM. The bigger print metal magazines tend to ignore records by NSBM bands.<ref name=\"akweb\"/> The book ''Unheilige Allianzen'' caused a short debate, leading ''Legacy'' magazine to stop printing ads for NSBM labels. Another debate happened in the \"letters\" section of ''Rock Hard'' magazine following the article ''Der rechte Rand im Black Metal'' (''Black Metal's Far-right Border'').<ref>M\u00fchlmann, Wolf-R\u00fcdiger: ''Der rechte Rand im Black Metal''. In: ''Rock Hard'', No. 241, June 2007, pp. 58\u201361.</ref>\n\n== Denial of identification ==\nSome bands have denied being labeled NSBM, and assert that they are either pagan or nationalist black metal. Official statements against this label have been made by bands such as [[Graveland]]. Akitsa, a group sometimes rumoured to be NSBM, made strong statements against the Nazi ideology and the whole NSBM genre.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vice.com/en_us/article/65z348/akitsa-grands-tyrans-interview-black-metal|title=Akitsa Are 'Grands Tyrans': An Interview on Their History, Purity in Black Metal, and Squashing NSBM Rumors|last=Vesin|first=Fran\u00e7ois|date=2015-05-29|website=[[Vice (magazine)|Vice]]|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.graveland.org/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=351:graveland-is-not-an-nsbm&catid=3:news-home&Itemid=1|title=GRAVELAND IS NOT AN NSBM!|last=Darken|first=Rob|website=www.graveland.org|language=en-gb|access-date=2017-09-24}}</ref> While some of these bands made statements which the scene and critics has taken as serious statements against nazism, other bands' statements has by many critics been viewed merely as a tactic; to be able to play live gigs, not be banned, and so on, such is the cases of Nokturnal Mortum and Graveland, among others, who has continued to openly support white supremacist organizers after making statements about being \"unpolitical\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://pov.international/militant-black-metal-i-denne-weekend-samles-hojreekstremister-fra-hele-verden-i-kiev/|title=Lige nu samles h\u00f8jreekstremister fra hele verden til festival i Kiev \u2022 POV|last=Hagen|first=Freddy|date=December 12, 2019|website=Point of View International|language=Danish|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref>\n\n==List of artists==\n{{dynamic list}}\n{{columns-list|colwidth=20em|\n*[[Absurd (band)|Absurd]]<ref name=semenyaka>{{cite web|last1=Semenyaka|first1=Olena|title=When the gods hear the call: the conservative-revolutionary potential of Black Metal Art|url=http://politosophia.org/page/when-the-gods-hear-the-call.html|publisher=Politosophia|accessdate=July 13, 2016|date=January 3, 2013}}</ref><ref name=gods>{{cite book|last1=Gardell|first1=Mattias|authorlink1=Mattias Gardell|title=[[Gods of the Blood: The Pagan Revival and White Separatism]]|date=2003|publisher=[[Duke University Press]]|location=Durham, North Carolina|page=307|isbn=9780822330714}}</ref><ref>Dyck, Kristin, 2017. p. 47, 61-62</ref><ref name=\"noisey\">{{cite web |title=Nearly Every Major Online Retailer Is Selling White Power Music |url=https://www.vice.com/en_au/article/r3z8y8/online-music-retailers-selling-white-power-records |website=[[Vice Media|Noisey]] |accessdate=17 July 2019 |date=21 November 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"tablet\">{{cite web |last1=Schragin |first1=Adam |title=White Supremacists Are Using Black Metal to Promote Hate |url=https://www.tabletmag.com/jewish-arts-and-culture/music/156896/black-metal-antichrist-kramer |website=[[Tablet (magazine)|Tablet]] |accessdate=17 July 2019 |date=23 December 2013}}</ref>\n*Abusiveness<ref name=\"reichsrock1\">Dyck, Kirsten, 2017. p.109</ref>\n*Aryan Blood<ref name=\"hornung36\">{{cite book |last1=Hornung |first1=Sebastian |title=Medial inszenierte Misanthropie und Kulturpessimismus: Eine systematische Betrachtung der Black-Metal-Szene und Optionen medienp\u00e4dagogischen Handelns |date=2016 |publisher=[[LIT Verlag]] |location=[[M\u00fcnster]] |isbn=9783643133335 |pages=36, 86|language=German}}</ref>\n*Aryan Terrorism<ref name=\":6\" />\n*Baise ma Hache<ref>https://rouendanslarue.net/rouen-ivre-il-propose-a-des-neo-nazis-de-jouer-dans-sa-boite-de-nuit/</ref><ref>https://www.rockgegenrechts.org/watchblog/black-metal-konzert-mit-umstrittenen-bands/</ref>\n*Bannerwar<ref name=\"present tense\">{{cite journal |last1=Williams |first1=Jonathan F. |title=Burke, Black Metal, and the Golden Dawn: Deconstructing the Weaponized White Identity Politics of National Socialist Black Metal |journal=Present Tense |date=2 May 2018 |volume=7 |issue=1 |url=http://www.presenttensejournal.org/volume-7/burke-black-metal-and-the-golden-dawn-deconstructing-the-dangerous-appeal-of-national-socialist-black-metal/ |accessdate=17 July 2019}}</ref>\n*Before God<ref name=\"dyck62\">Dyck, Kirsten, 2017. p.62</ref>\n*Bilksirnir<ref name=\"noisey\" /><ref name=\":7\">Dyck, Kristin, 2017. p. 47</ref>\n*[[Burzum]]<ref name=\":4\">Dyck, Kirsten, 2017. p.60</ref>\n*Dark Fury<ref name=\"newyorker\">{{cite web |last1=Moynihan |first1=Colin |title=Metal Confronts Its Nazi Problem |url=https://www.newyorker.com/culture/culture-desk/heavy-metal-confronts-its-nazi-problem |website=[[The New Yorker]] |accessdate=17 July 2019 |date=19 February 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"reichsrock1\" />\n*Der St\u00fcrmer<ref name=\"newyorker\" /><ref name=\"tablet\" /><ref name=\"present tense\" /><ref>Hornung, Sebastian, 2016. p.36, 84</ref>\n*[[Drudkh]]<ref name=semenyaka /><ref name=\":8\">Patterson, Dayal, 2013. p. 366, 411</ref>\n*Eugenik<ref name=\":7\" />\n*Evil<ref name=\":2\" />\n*Forest<ref name=\":8\" />\n*Gestapo 666<ref name=\"noisey\" />\n*Gestapo SS<ref>Dyck, Kirsten, 2017. p.122</ref>\n*[[Goatmoon]]<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\"newyorker\" /><ref name=\":2\" /><ref>{{cite web|title=Neo-Nazi Concert in Tampere Sparks Concern|url=http://yle.fi/uutiset/osasto/news/neo-nazi_concert_in_tampere_sparks_concern/5821037|website=[[YLE|YLE News]]|accessdate=January 9, 2017|date=January 2, 2008}}{{cite web|title=Report: 'Neo-Nazi' Black Metal Concert In Finland Sparks Concern|url=http://www.blabbermouth.net/news/report-neo-nazi-black-metal-concert-in-finland-sparks-concern/|website=[[Blabbermouth.net]]|publisher=[[Roadrunner Records]]|accessdate=January 9, 2017|date=February 1, 2008}}</ref>\n*Gontayna Kry<ref name=\"reichsrock1\" /><ref name=\":9\" />\n*[[Grand Belial's Key]]<ref name=\"noisey\" /><ref name=decibel>{{Cite web|url=http://www.decibelmagazine.com/features/may2006/nsbm.aspx|title=NSBM Special Report|last=Bennett|first=J.|date=May 2006|website=[[Decibel (magazine)|Decibel]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080208184453/http://www.decibelmagazine.com/features/may2006/nsbm.aspx|archive-date=8 February 2008|access-date=17 July 2019}}</ref>\n*[[Graveland]]{{efn|Graveland was central to the Polish NSBM scene and has been labeled as NSBM.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\"Hornung84\">Hornung, Sebastian, 2016. p.84</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Aitkens |first1=Chris |title=The Darker Side of Metal: Racism |url=http://www.cjlo.com/articles/darker-side-metal-racism-1 |website=[[CJLO]] |accessdate=17 July 2019 |date=1 April 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"robdarken\">Dyck, Kirsten, 2017. p.108</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Kelly |first1=Kim |title=The Shade And The Light: Nergal Of Behemoth Interviewed |url=https://thequietus.com/articles/14452-nergal-interview-behemoth |website=[[The Quietus]] |accessdate=17 July 2019 |date=10 February 2014}}</ref><ref name=\":8\" /> The band itself disputes this label and its lyrics avoid political subjects.<ref name=\"newyorker\" /><ref>{{cite web |last1=Islander |title=Shades of Black: Antaeus, Afar, Enepsigos, Graveland, Gravespawn, Nebrus, Stroda, Surtr |url=https://www.nocleansinging.com/2016/10/30/shades-of-black-antaeus-afar-enepsigos-graveland-gravespawn-nebrus-stroda-surtr/ |website=No Clean Singing |accessdate=17 July 2019 |date=30 October 2016}}</ref> Rob Darken from the band has said: \"I do not think Graveland is an NSBM band. Graveland is regarded as a NSBM band because of my political convictions, [which] most people would call extreme right-wing National Socialist convictions.\"<ref name=decibel />}}\n*Grom<ref name=decibel />\n*[[Hate Forest]]<ref name=semenyaka /><ref name=\":8\" />\n*[[Infernum]]<ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\":9\">Patterson, Dayal, 2013. p. 364</ref><ref name=thunderbolt>{{cite web |last1=Kalis |first1=Quentin |title=Diabolic Revelations |url=http://www.chroniclesofchaos.com/articles.aspx?id=1-815 |website=Chronicles of Chaos |accessdate=19 July 2019 |date=21 July 2005}}</ref>\n*Kalmankantajah<ref name=\":1a\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.heraldscotland.com/news/18279354.glasgow-metal-festival-organiser-denies-bands-bill-links-neo-nazis/|title=Glasgow metal festival organiser denies bands on bill have links with neo-nazis|last=Learmonth|first=Andrew|date=March 4|website=[[The Herald (Glasgow)|The Herald]]|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref>\n*Kataxu<ref name=\":9\" />\n*Kristallnacht<ref name=\"noisey\" />\n*[[Kroda]]<ref name=\":2\" /><ref name=semenyaka /><ref name=\":8\" /><ref name=\":1a\" />\n*Leichenzug<ref>Hornung, Sebastian, 2016. p.86</ref>\n*Lord Wind<ref name=\"robdarken\" />\n*\u041c8\u041b8\u0422\u0425<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\"newyorker\" /><ref name=\":2\" /><ref name=\":1a\" />\n*Menneskerhat<ref name=\"hornung36\" />\n*[[Naer Mataron]]<ref name=\"present tense\" />\n*Nacht Und Nebel<ref name=decibel />\n*Nitberg<ref name=\":8\" />\n*Nocturnal Depression<ref name=\":1a\" />\n*[[Nokturnal Mortum]]<ref name=semenyaka /><ref name=\":8\" />\n*Patris<ref name=\"present tense\" />\n*[[Peste Noire]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.chroniclesofchaos.com/articles.aspx?id=2-6343|title=CoC : Peste Noire - L'Ordure \u00e0 l'\u00c9tat Pur : Review|last=Carbon|first=Johnathan A.|date=July 23, 2011|website=[[Chronicles of Chaos (webzine)|Chronicles of Chaos]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref>\n*[[RaHoWa (band)|RaHoWa]]<ref>Dyck, Kirsten, 2017. p.62, 115</ref>{{efn|RaHoWa experimented with an NSBM sound on its second album}}\n*Reich of the Black Sun<ref name=\"hornung36\" />\n*[[Satanic Warmaster]]<ref name=\"noisey\" /><ref>{{cite news |title=\"Neo-Nazi\" Band Satanic Warmaster Have Announced Their First UK Gig in Glasgow, and People Are Pissed |url=https://www.vice.com/en_us/article/rq4b9m/satanic-warmaster-and-their-glasgow-controversy |accessdate=5 February 2020 |work=Vice |date=27 April 2015 |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Paterson |first1=Kirsteen |title=Band linked to neo-Nazis play secret Glasgow gig |url=https://www.thenational.scot/news/14901718.band-linked-to-neo-nazis-play-secret-glasgow-gig/ |accessdate=5 February 2020 |work=The National |date=11 February 2016 |language=en |quote=Satanic Warmaster have been criticised for songs like \u201cGas Chamber\u201d and lyrics which include the phrase \u201cSieg Heil!\u201d and refer to \u201ctorching the Jewish creation\u201d.}}</ref>{{efn|Satanic Warmaster has shunned the NSBM label as a band. Front-man and currently the only member \"Werwolf\" stated in 2015 that \"Personally, I could never tie Satanic Warmaster down to the concept of NSBM for the reasons that have been there from 1998: It would not coincide with my conviction and the thoughts I want to convey through my music... the ideology behind Satanic Warmaster is Satanism and the musical style is black metal. Those, who claim otherwise, do it on the basis of their own feelings and resentment.\"<ref>{{cite web |last1=Ahola |first1=Tapio |title=Satanic Warmaster \u2013 Majesteettista julistusta m\u00e4t\u00e4ist\u00e4 valtavirtaa vastaan |url=https://www.rumba.fi/haastattelut/satanic-warmaster-majesteettista-julistusta-mataista-valtavirtaa-vastaan/ |website=Rumba |accessdate=17 July 2019 |language=Finnish |date=7 January 2015}}</ref>}}\n*Seigneur Voland<ref name=\":2\" /><ref name=\":5\" />\n*Selbstmord<ref name=\"reichsrock1\" />\n*Sokyra Peruna<ref name=\":0\" />\n*Spear of Longinus<ref name=\"noisey\" /><ref name=decibel />\n*Stahlfront<ref name=\"newyorker\" />\n*Stutthof<ref name=\":2\" /><ref name=\":5\" />\n*Sunwheel<ref name=\"newyorker\" />\n*Temnozor<ref name=\":8\" />\n*Thor's Hammer<ref name=\":9\" /><ref name=decibel />\n*Thunderbolt<ref name=\"dyck62\" />{{efn|The band was active in the NSBM scene but has since rejected the genre in favor of Satanism. Band member Paimon stated in a 2005 interview that \"We have -nothing- in common with this so-called 'NSBM' scene since five years or so... Our involvement in the 'NSBM' scene is the past and we're not a part of it anymore.\"<ref name=thunderbolt />}}\n*Totenburg<ref name=\":7\" /><ref>Hornung, Sebastian, 2016. p.36, 84, 86</ref>\n*Ulfhethnar<ref name=\":7\" />\n*Veles<ref name=\":9\" />\n*Wehrhammer<ref name=\"present tense\" />\n*Wodulf<ref name=\":2\" /><ref name=\":5\" />\n*Wolfnacht<ref name=\"present tense\" />\n}}\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Asgardsrei festival]]\n* [[Nazi punk]]\n* [[Rock Against Communism]]\n* [[Neo-v\u00f6lkisch movements]]\n* [[Nazi occultism]]\n* [[White nationalism]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n\n=== English ===\n* [[Nicholas Goodrick-Clarke]]: ''White Noise and black metal'' in: ''Black Sun: Aryan Cults, Esoteric Nazism and the Politics of Identity'' (S. 193\u2013213). New York University Press, 2002, {{ISBN|0-8147-3124-4}}\n* [[Mattias Gardell]]: ''Hail Loki! Hail Satan! Hail Hitler! Darkside Asatr\u00fa, Satanism and Occult National Socialism'' in: ''[[Gods of the Blood|Gods of the Blood: The Pagan Revival and White Separatism]]''. (pp.&nbsp;284\u2013324). Duke University Press, 2003, {{ISBN|0-8223-3071-7}}\n* {{cite book |last1=Moynihan |first1=Michael |author1-link=Michael Moynihan (journalist) |last2=S\u00f8derlind |first2=Didrik |title=[[Lords of Chaos (book)|Lords of Chaos: The Bloody Rise of the Satanic Metal Underground]] |edition=Revised and expanded |year=2003 |origyear=1998 |publisher=Feral House |isbn= |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |last=Olson |first=Benjamin Hedge |date=May 2008 |title=I Am the Black Wizards: Multiplicity, Mysticism and Identity in Black Metal Music and Culture |publisher=Bowling Green State University |url=http://etd.ohiolink.edu/send-pdf.cgi/Olson%20Benjamin%20Hedge.pdf?bgsu1206132032 |ref=harv}}\n\n=== German ===\n* Christian Dornbusch, Hans-Peter Killguss: ''Unheilige Allianzen. Black Metal zwischen Satanismus, Heidentum und Neonazismus''. M\u00fcnster, Unrast Verlag, 2005, {{ISBN|3-89771-817-0}}\n* Johannes Lohmann, Hans Wanders: ''Evolas J\u00fcnger und Odins Krieger \u2013 Extrem rechte Ideologien in der Dark-Wave- und Black-Metal-Szene'' in: Christian Dornbusch, Jan Raabe: ''RechtsRock \u2013 Bestandsaufnahme und Gegenstrategien''. (p.&nbsp;287\u2013311) Hamburg/M\u00fcnster, Unrast Verlag, 2002, {{ISBN|3-89771-808-1}}.\n\n{{White Nationalism}}\n{{Alt-right}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:National Socialist Black Metal}}\n[[Category:National Socialist black metal| ]]\n[[Category:Black metal subgenres]]\n[[Category:Black metal controversies]]\n[[Category:Neo-Nazi music]]\n[[Category:Neo-Nazism]]\n[[Category:Obscenity controversies in music]]\n[[Category:Alt-right]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox music genre\n| name              = National Socialist black metal\n| bgcolor           = #BB0022\n| color             = white\n| stylistic_origins = * [[Black metal]]\n* [[pagan metal]]\n* [[Rock Against Communism]]\n* [[Nazi punk|hatecore]]\n| cultural_origins  = Early 1990s to present, [[Europe]]\n| instruments       = * [[Singing|Vocals]]\n* [[electric guitar]]\n* [[bass guitar]]\n* [[Drum kit|drums]]\n| popularity        = Underground\n| other_topics      = *[[White power skinhead]]\n}}\n{{Nazism sidebar}}\n\n'''National Socialist black metal''', also known as '''NSBM''', '''Aryan black metal''' or '''Neo-Nazi black metal''', is a political movement within [[black metal]] music that promotes [[neo-Nazism]] and similar ideologies. NSBM artists typically combine neo-Nazi imagery and ideology with [[Paganism#Historical paganism|ethnic European paganism]], [[Satanism]], or [[Nazism and occultism|Nazi occultism]], and vehemently oppose [[Christianity]], [[Islam]] and [[Judaism]]. NSBM is not seen as a distinct genre, but as a [[neo-v\u00f6lkisch movements|neo-v\u00f6lkisch movement]] within black metal. According to [[Mattias Gardell]], NSBM musicians see this ideology as \"a logical extension of the political and spiritual dissidence inherent in black metal\".<ref name=\"Gardell\">Mattias Gardell, [[Gods of the Blood|''Gods of the Blood'' (2003)]], p.307</ref>\n\nAlthough there is an undercurrent of ethnic nationalism in black metal,{{sfn|Moynihan|S\u00f8derlind|2003|p=349-355}}<ref name=\"Gardell\"/><ref>{{cite journal |ref=harv |last1=Trafford |first1=Simon |last2=Pluskowski |first2=Aleks |editor-last=Marshall |editor-first=David W. |year=2007 |title=Antichrist Superstars: The Vikings in Hard Rock and Heavy Metal |url=https://www.academia.edu/521897/Antichrist_Superstars_The_Vikings_in_hard_rock_and_heavy_metal |journal=Mass Market Medieval: Essays on the Middle Ages in Popular Culture |publisher=[[McFarland & Company]] |pages=64 |isbn=978-0-7864-2922-6 }}</ref> NSBM artists are a small minority within the genre.<ref name=\"Gardell\"/>{{sfn|Olson|2008|p=123f}} NSBM artists are not always explicit with their political beliefs in the music, instead expressing their beliefs offstage.<ref name=reichsrock>{{cite book|last1=Dyck|first1=Kirsten|title=Reichsrock: The International Web of White-Power and Neo-Nazi Hate Music|date=2016|publisher=[[Rutgers University Press]]|location=New Brunswick|isbn=9780813574738|pages=58\u201361|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=sREVDQAAQBAJ&source=gbs_navlinks_s|accessdate=January 9, 2017}}</ref> Artists who hold [[Far-right politics|far-right]] or [[White nationalism|white nationalist]] beliefs but do not express these in their music are not often deemed NSBM by the greater black metal scene, but may be labelled as such by outside analysts.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bifff-berlin.de/aktuell72.html |title=Rechtes Neuheiden-Festival mit Nazi-Runen im \"SO 36\" |publisher=BIFFF ...|language=de}}</ref> Some black metal bands have also made references to [[Nazi Germany]] purely for [[shock value]], much like some [[punk rock]] and [[heavy metal music|heavy metal]] bands. While some black-metallers boycott NSBM artists, many are indifferent or appreciate the music without supporting the musicians.{{sfn|Olson|2008|p=99}} According to Christian Dornbusch and Hans-Peter Killguss's 2005 book ''Unheilige Allianzen'', v\u00f6lkisch [[pagan metal]] and neo-Nazism were the current trends in black metal, and in turn were affecting the broader metal scene.<ref>''Unheilige Allianzen'', p. 290. {{ISBN|3-89771-817-0}}</ref>\n\nThe emergence of NSBM coincided with the rise of the [[early Norwegian black metal scene]] in the early 1990s, particularly through the band [[Burzum]], whose sole member, [[Varg Vikernes]], developed his [[Satanism|Satanist]] beliefs and antagonism to Christianity into an increasingly white nationalist and neo-Nazi form of [[Heathenry (new religious movement)|Heathenry]]. The German band [[Absurd (band)|Absurd]] further developed the burgeoning scene with explicitly neo-Nazi lyrics and artistic themes.  The movement became especially popular in Eastern Europe, where it was developed by bands such as the Polish groups [[Graveland]] and [[Infernum]] and the Ukrainian band [[Hate Forest]]. The United States bands [[Grand Belial's Key]] and [[Judas Iscariot (band)|Judas Iscariot]] also became involved in the by-now international NSBM movement. As the movement grew internationally, it started to overlap with existing white supremacist and neo-Nazi musical forms such as [[Rock Against Communism]], [[Nazi punk|hatecore]], and the far-fight faction of [[Oi!]]. The Canadian neo-Nazi record label [[Resistance Records]] started releasing NSBM recordings, and even purchased Vikernes' label Cymophane Records. The United States white supremacist [[William Luther Pierce]] and his political organization [[National Alliance (United States)|National Alliance]] also became interested in the movement, and assisted Absurd frontman Hendrik M\u00f6bus when he fled to the United States to avoid arrest in Germany. In the early 2000s, bands such the Ukrainian [[Drudkh]] and [[Kroda]] and the Russian \u041c8\u041b8\u0422\u0425 continued the scene's popularity in Eastern Europe. In 2012, the NSBM [[Asgardsrei festival]] was established in [[Moscow]], Russia, and then in 2014 relocated to [[Kiev]], Ukraine, where it is closely linked to the activities of the [[Ukrainian nationalism|Ukrainian nationalist]] network [[Azov Battalion]] and functions as an international hub for neo-Nazism and other far-right politics.\n\n==Black metal==\n{{Main|Black metal}}\nBlack metal is a style of [[extreme metal]] music. Common traits include [[Tempo#Beats per minute|fast tempos]], a [[Screaming (music)#Black metal|shrieking]] vocal style,<ref name=metalsucks>{{cite web | url=http://www.metalsucks.net/2012/11/08/vons-satanic-blood-black-black-black-black-no-1/ | title=Von's Satanic Blood: Black Black Black Black No. 1 | publisher=[[MetalSucks]] | date=8 November 2012 | accessdate=8 May 2013 | author=O'Hagar, Sammy}}</ref><ref name=allmusic>{{cite web |url={{Allmusic|class=album|id=inri-mw0000243175|pure_url=yes}} |title=((( I.N.R.I. > Overview ))) |author=Rivadavia, Eduardo |website=[[AllMusic]] |accessdate=2007-12-18}}</ref><ref name=Sputnikmusic>{{cite web|last=Freeman|first=Channing|title=Album Review - Darkthrone: A Blaze in the Northern Sky|url=https://www.sputnikmusic.com/review/54469/Darkthrone-A-Blaze-in-the-Northern-Sky/|website=[[Sputnikmusic]]|accessdate=22 January 2013|date=18 January 2013}}</ref> heavily distorted [[Electric guitar|guitars]] played with [[tremolo picking]], raw ([[Lo-fi music|lo-fi]]) recording, unconventional [[song structure]]s, and an emphasis on atmosphere. Artists often appear in [[corpse paint]] and adopt pseudonyms. During the 1980s, several [[thrash metal|thrash]] and [[death metal]] bands formed a prototype for black metal.<ref name=\"Stylus Magazine\">{{cite magazine |url=http://www.stylusmagazine.com/articles/weekly_article/into-the-void-stylus-magazines-beginners-guide-to-metal.htm |title=Into the void: Stylus Magazine's Beginner's Guide to Metal |last1=Lee |first1=Cosmo |last2=Voegtlin |first2=Stewart |magazine=[[Stylus Magazine]] |accessdate=17 May 2010}}</ref> Initially a synonym for \"Satanic metal,\"<ref>{{cite book |last=McIver |first=Joel |authorlink=Joel McIver |title=Justice for All - The Truth About Metallica |edition=updated |publisher=Omnibus Press |year=2009 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=SvW-uN-qEbIC&pg=PT98&dq=%22black+metal%22#v=onepage&q=%22black%20metal%22&f=false |accessdate=4 September 2012}}</ref> black metal is often met with hostility from mainstream culture, due to the actions and [[Black metal#Ideology|ideologies]] associated with it. Many artists express extreme [[Anti-Christian sentiment|anti-Christian]] and [[Misanthropy|misanthropic]] views, advocating various forms of [[Satanism]] or [[Polytheistic reconstructionism|ethnic paganism]]. In the 1990s, members of the scene were responsible for a spate of [[Black metal#Church burnings|church burnings]] and murders. There is also a small neo-Nazi movement within black metal, although it has been shunned by many prominent artists.<ref name=billzebub/><ref name=kingovhell>{{cite web |url=http://www.maelstrom.nu/ezine/interview_iss50_224.php |title=Interview with Jotunspor |last=\u0160kot |first=Mladen |work=maelstrom.nu |accessdate=4 September 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110927131014/http://www.maelstrom.nu/ezine/interview_iss50_224.php |archivedate=27 September 2011 }}</ref><ref name=infernus1>{{cite web |url=http://www.roadrunnerrecords.com/blabbermouth.Net/news.aspx?mode=Article&newsitemID=93004 |title=Blabbermouth.net - Gorgoroth Guitarist Infernus: 'I Personally Am Against Racism in Both Thought and Practice' |date=15 March 2008 |work=[[Blabbermouth.net]] |accessdate=4 September 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090422024415/http://www.roadrunnerrecords.com/blabbermouth.Net/news.aspx?mode=Article&newsitemID=93004 |archivedate=22 April 2009 }}</ref> Generally, black metal strives to remain [[Underground music|underground]], inaccessible to the mainstream.{{sfn|Olson|2008|p=30}}\n\n== History ==\n{{Listen\n|filename = \u041b\u044e\u0442\u044c \u043d\u0430\u0448\u043e\u0457 \u0432\u0456\u0442\u0447\u0438\u0437\u043d\u0438.ogg\n|title = \u00ab\u0406\u0434\u0443 \u043d\u0430 \u0432\u0438!\u00bb (2002)\n|description = \u00ab\u041b\u044e\u0442\u044c \u043d\u0430\u0448\u043e\u0457 \u0432\u0456\u0442\u0447\u0438\u0437\u043d\u0438\u00bb, demonstrating NSBM\n}}\nIn the 1980s, 'black metal' referred to heavy metal bands with Satanic lyrics and imagery. Black metal originated with the band [[Venom (band)|Venom]] out of [[Newcastle upon Tyne|Newcastle]], [[England]]. Their debut album ''[[Welcome to Hell|Welcome To Hell]]'' released in 1981 and was followed by 1982's ''[[Black metal|Black Metal]]''. Venom's image lyrics and musical style were copied and inspired by bands such as [[Slayer]], [[Hellhammer]], [[Celtic Frost]], [[Bathory (band)|Bathory]], [[Exodus (American band)|Exodus]], and [[Possessed (band)|Possessed]]. In the early 1990s, the [[early Norwegian black metal scene]] developed the style into a distinct genre. The scene members were fiercely [[Criticism of Christianity|anti-Christian]] and generally presented themselves as [[misanthropy|misanthropic]] [[Theistic Satanism|Devil-worshipers]] who wanted to spread hatred, sorrow and evil. However, some bands wrote about pre-Christian Scandinavia and its folklore. In 1992, members of the scene burnt down a number of churches. In August of the same year, [[Faust (musician)|Faust]] of [[Emperor (band)|Emperor]] killed a gay man who had propositioned him in [[Lillehammer]]. In August 1993, [[Varg Vikernes]] of [[Burzum]] killed fellow musician [[Euronymous]] \u2013 a well-known figure in the scene \u2013 and was arrested shortly after. Euronymous was said to be a [[communism|communist]], but Vikernes denies killing him over ideology. Although Vikernes's music was never explicitly political, he began to express neo-Nazi views in writings and interviews after his arrest.\n\nVikernes is generally seen as being responsible for popularizing such views in the black metal scene. According to an interview in ''Blood & Honour'' magazine, he contacted neo-Nazi organization Zorn 88 (later called the [[National Socialist Movement of Norway]]) in 1992<ref name=\"Unheiligepage277\">''Unheilige Allianzen'', p. 277.</ref> and joined White Aryan Resistance before he killed Euronymous.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.berlinonline.de/berliner-zeitung/archiv/.bin/dump.fcgi/1996/0902/reporter/0002/?subnav=Spezial|archive-url=https://archive.is/20120723205956/http://www.berlinonline.de/berliner-zeitung/archiv/.bin/dump.fcgi/1996/0902/reporter/0002/?subnav=Spezial|url-status=dead|archive-date=23 July 2012|title=Aktuell|website=www.berlinonline.de|accessdate=29 August 2017}}</ref> While in prison, \"Vikernes began to formulate his nationalist heathen ideology\"<ref>Goodrick-Clarke, p. 204.</ref> and wrote a manifesto called ''Vargsm\u00e5l''. It became available on the internet for a while in 1996,<ref>''Lords of Chaos'', p. 159.</ref> and in 1997 it was printed by a Norwegian publisher.{{citation needed|date=February 2017}}  By 2004, Vikernes abandoned playing metal music because of its origin as \"Negro music\", and argued that the 'metal heads' tend to behave like a bunch of 'White Niggers', so to speak, with their sex, drugs and rock'n'roll culture.\"<ref name=\":3\" />\n\nSome other members of the early Norwegian scene explored with Nazi themes and imagery, but this was partly an attempt to provoke listeners.{{sfn|Olson|2008|p=101}} Vikernes later claimed that the scene had begun \"as a nationalistic (Norwegian-centric), racist and anti-Christian revolt\" but was \"hijacked\" by the \"Jew-dominated music industry\". He claims the industry made it into another tool with which to destroy Europe, by promoting bands who embraced \"everything sick and anti-European on this planet, from porn and promiscuity to drugs and homosexuality\".<ref>Vikernes, Varg. [http://thuleanperspective.com/2013/03/07/how-to-revolt-in-practise-ii/ \"How to revolt in practise II] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130311135742/http://thuleanperspective.com/2013/03/07/how-to-revolt-in-practise-ii/ |date=2013-03-11 }}\". Thulean Perspective. 7 March 2013.</ref> Hendrik M\u00f6bus of [[Absurd (band)|Absurd]] called NSBM the \"logical conclusion\" of the Norwegian black metal movement and interpreted the church burnings as a \"cultural [[atavism]]\".<ref name=\"M\u00f6bus\"/>\n\nVikernes wrote some lyrics for the album ''[[Transilvanian Hunger]]'' by [[Darkthrone]], another key band in the Norwegian scene. It was released in 1994 with ''Norsk Arisk Black Metal'' ('Norwegian Aryan Black Metal') printed on the back cover. This caused much controversy, and Darkthrone claimed that they were \"not a Nazi band nor a political band\".<ref name=\"MusicMight biography\">{{cite web |url=http://www.musicmight.com/artist/norway/kolbotn/darkthrone |title=MusicMight :: Artists :: Darkthrone |work=[[MusicMight]] |accessdate=23 September 2012}}</ref> In a 2007 documentary, [[Fenriz]] claimed he was once arrested while participating in an anti-[[apartheid]] demonstration and later had a \"phase of being really angry with&nbsp;... other races\" before he became \"totally unengaged in [political] shit\".<ref name=\"billzebub2\">Zebub, Bill (2007). ''Black Metal: A Documentary''.</ref>\n\nAt around this time, some other Scandinavian black-metallers made racist statements and utilized Nazi paraphernalia. In 1994, [[Jan Axel Blomberg|Hellhammer]], the drummer for the Norwegian band [[Mayhem (band)|Mayhem]], said of the genre's links with racism: \"I'll put it this way, we don't like black people here. Black Metal is for white people\".<ref>''Lords of Chaos'', p. 351.</ref> When Mayhem re-formed after Euronymous's death, they began releasing merchandise bearing World War II-era [[Nazi symbolism|Nazi symbols]].<ref>[http://www.blabbermouth.net/news/mayhem-frontman-says-varg-vikernes-is-very-polite-and-kind/ Mayhem Frontman Says Varg Vikernes Is 'Very Polite And Kind']. [[Blabbermouth.net]]. 26 January 2010.</ref> However, in a later interview, Hellhammer said \"I don't give a crap if the fans are white, black, green, yellow, or blue. For me music and politics don't go hand in hand\".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://thydoom.com/en/interviews/6.html |title=ThyDoom.com |publisher=ThyDoom.com |accessdate=2011-10-06 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101002121928/http://thydoom.com/en/interviews/6.html |archivedate=2010-10-02 }}</ref> In 1995, prominent Norwegian black metal vocalist [[Gaahl]] described \"niggers\" and \"mulattoes\" as \"subhuman\" and stated his admiration for Vikernes and Adolf Hitler. However, he too has since distanced himself from these statements.<ref name=\"rockhardgaahl\">{{cite web |url=http://www.roadrunnerrecords.com/blabbermouth.net/news.aspx?mode=Article&newsitemID=107859 |title=BLABBERMOUTH.NET \u2013 GORGOROTH Frontman Opens Up About His Sexual Orientation: 'I've Never Made Any Secret About It' |publisher=Roadrunnerrecords.com |accessdate=2012-02-10 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111121222135/http://www.roadrunnerrecords.com/blabbermouth.net/news.aspx?mode=Article&newsitemID=107859 |archivedate=2011-11-21 }}</ref>  Gaahl was voted Gay Person of the Year in 2010 in Bergen.<ref name=\"Trelldom interview\">{{cite web|url=http://www.gorgoroth.com.pl/english/art-interview_with_gaahl_from_polish_holocaust_magazine_1995|archive-url=https://archive.is/20130416072609/http://www.gorgoroth.com.pl/english/art-interview_with_gaahl_from_polish_holocaust_magazine_1995|url-status=dead|archive-date=16 April 2013|title=Interview with Gaahl|accessdate=29 August 2017}}</ref> According to the authors of ''Lords of Chaos'', in 1995, three Swedish black-metallers (including Mika \"Belfagor\" Hakola of the band [[Nefandus]]) went on a \"niggerhunt\" in [[Link\u00f6ping]]. Wielding an axe and two machetes, they \"terrorized\" a black man.<ref>''Lords of Chaos'', pp. 308\u2013309.</ref> Nefandus were later \"considered to be Nazi sympathizers\", though Belfagor explained: \"This could not be further from the truth, but I guess this has to do with some of the controversial comments I made in various magazines in my youth, when I still aspired to play in the most hated band in the world. I used a lot of provocative language back then. But to sort things out: I associate with people of all creeds and colours. ... So to be labeled a Nazi or a racist is very offensive to me\".<ref>Terry Demeter: ''Ofermod''. ''Breath of the Dragon''. In: ''Unrestrained Magazine'', no. 39, p. 74.</ref>\n\nOne of the first explicitly NSBM releases was the 1995 demo ''Thuringian Pagan Madness'' by German band [[Absurd (band)|Absurd]]. It was recorded while the members were imprisoned for murdering a boy from their school. On the demo cover is a photograph of his gravestone and pro-Nazi statements.<ref>[[Nicholas Goodrick-Clarke]]: ''Black Sun: Aryan Cults, Esoteric Nazism, and the Politics of Identity''. NYU Press, 2003. p. 206.</ref> Other bands deemed to be part of the early NSBM scene include [[Graveland]], and [[Infernum]] (from [[Poland]]),<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.decibelmagazine.com/2013/05/13/interview-author-dayal-patterson-on-black-metal-evolution-of-the-cult/|title=INTERVIEW: Author Dayal Patterson on Black Metal: Evolution of the Cult|last=Horsley|first=Jonathan|date=2013-05-13|website=[[Decibel (magazine)|Decibel]]|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref> Branikald (from [[Russia]]), and [[Spear of Longinus (band)|Spear of Longinus]] and [[Waffenbr\u00fcder]] (from [[Australia]]). Rob Darken of Graveland in particular was a very central figure in the development of NSBM in Poland.<ref name=\":1\" /> In the 1990s, some of the earliest American black metal bands\u2014like [[Grand Belial's Key]] and [[Judas Iscariot (band)|Judas Iscariot]]\u2014joined an international NSBM organization called the Pagan Front, although Judas Iscariot's sole member [[Andrew Harris (musician)|Akhenaten]] left the organization.<ref name=\"mh82007\">Gunnar Sauermann: ''Special: Black Metal in den USA''. ''Schwarzes Amerika''. In: ''[[Metal Hammer]] Germany'', August 2007, p. 88.</ref> Thelemnar, the drummer of German band [[Secrets of the Moon]], said he got to know him \"only as an intelligent person and never as a Nazi\".<ref name=\"mh82007 />\n\nIn 2012, Alexey Levkin, frontman of the band \u041c8\u041b8\u0422\u0425, along with others, started the NSBM music festival [[Asgardsrei festival|Asgardsrei]] in [[Moscow]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://militant.zone/ar2017/|title=ASGARDSREI 2017 \u2013 Absurd, Peste Noire, Goatmoon, Naer Mataron, M8L8TH, Burshtyn (Kiev, 16.12.2017) {{!}} Militant Zone|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref><ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.bellingcat.com/news/2020/01/02/dispatches-from-asgardsrei-ukraines-annual-neo-nazi-music-festival/|title=Dispatches From Asgardsrei: Ukraine\u2019s Annual Neo-Nazi Music Festival|last=Colborne|first=Michael|date=2020-01-02|website=[[Bellingcat]]|language=en-GB|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref> The event is named after the 1999 album of the same name by Absurd.<ref name=\"newyorker\" /> The festival was relocated to [[Kiev]] in 2014 when Levkin and the other organizers relocated to [[Ukraine]] to join the [[Azov Battalion]].<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":2\">{{Cite news|last=Colborne|first=Michael|url=https://www.haaretz.com/world-news/europe/.premium-most-neo-nazi-music-festivals-are-closely-guarded-secrets-not-this-one-1.8260218|title=Most neo-Nazi Music Festivals Are Closely Guarded Secrets \u2014 Not This One in Ukraine|date=2019-12-12|work=[[Haaretz]]|access-date=2020-04-08|url-status=live|language=en}}</ref>\n\n== Ideology ==\nNSBM typically melds Neo-Nazi beliefs (such as [[fascism]], [[white supremacy]], [[white separatism]], [[white nationalism]], [[Far-right politics|right-wing extremism]], [[antisemitism]], [[xenophobia]], [[ethnic separatism]], with some [[National-anarchism|National-anarchist]] tendencies and admiration of [[Adolf Hitler]]) with hostility to \"foreign\" religions. Bands often promote ethnic European paganism, occultism, or Satanism. Hendrik M\u00f6bus of Absurd described Nazism as the \"most perfect (and only realistic!) synthesis of Satanic/[[Luciferianism|Luciferian]] [[will to power]], elitist [[Social Darwinism]], connected to Aryan [[Germanic paganism]]\".<ref>Stormblast, Nr. 2-3, 1999, citation taken from [http://www.akweb.de/ak_s/ak428/31.htm ak \u2013 analyse & kritik \u2013 zeitung f\u00fcr linke Debatte und Praxis / Nr. 428 / 8.7.1999]</ref> Members of the band Der St\u00fcrmer (named after the [[Der St\u00fcrmer|antisemitic newspaper]] edited by [[Julius Streicher]]) subscribe to [[Esoteric Nazism]], leaning on the works of [[Savitri Devi]] and [[Julius Evola]].<ref name=\"LEGEONES\">{{cite web|url=http://www.thepaganfront.com/dersturmer/interviews/LEGEONES.html|title=Der St\u00fcrmer interview published in LEGEONES magazine|publisher=|accessdate=29 August 2017}}</ref> Famine of [[Peste Noire]] stated in an interview that he prefers [[Italian Fascism]] instead of [[Nazism]] as an ideology.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.lamesnieherlequin.com/2014/07/translation-of-the-kpn-interview-for-cercle-non-conforme/,%20https://www.lamesnieherlequin.com/2014/07/translation-of-the-kpn-interview-for-cercle-non-conforme/|title=La Mesnie Herlequin \u00bb English translation of the PESTE NOIRE interview for Cercle Non Conforme|last=Cercle Non Conforme|first=|date=July 22, 2014|website=|others=Translated by M.D.L. and L\u2019Atrabilaire|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref>\n\n=== Anti-Christianity and antisemitism ===\nTypically NSBM musicians regard Christianity as a product of an alleged [[Jewish conspiracy]] to undermine the [[Aryan race]] by eliminating their ''Artglauben'' and their \"original\" culture.<ref name=\"akweb\">{{cite web|url=http://www.akweb.de/ak_s/ak428/31.htm|title=ak 428: Unheilige Allianz|website=www.akweb.de|accessdate=29 August 2017}}</ref> These musicians usually reject the legitimacy of [[Christianity and antisemitism|Christian antisemitism]] as well as the [[German Christians]] movement, which celebrated and promoted Nazi ideology in the context of an unorthodox [[Christian theology|Christian theological]] framework. Hjarulv Henker of the band Der St\u00fcrmer said:\n{{quote|I don't think that a dogma like Christianity has a place in Aryandom. There is no way to make Christianity fit into the Weltanschauung of the Aryan Overman. Christianity teaches humbleness, the loss of National and Racial identity, and equality, things alien to our cosmotheory. You cannot combine Jesus with characters who represent Aryan ethics. ... Christianity is Christianity and it is Jewish by its very birth and conception, a vehicle in the Jewish world domination and designed as such.<ref name=\"LEGEONES\"/>}}\n\n=== White supremacy ===\nNSBM musicians such as Varg Vikernes of Burzum and Famine of Peste Noire have expressed a white supremacist concern about \"[[Miscegenation|race mixing]]\" and preserving the purity of the [[white race]] and the traditional cultures of white European nations.<ref name=\":3\">{{cite web|url=http://www.burzum.org/eng/library/interview01.shtml|title=Interview with Varg Vikernes|last=BG|first=|date=August 12, 2004|website=www.burzum.org|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|accessdate=29 August 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.lamag.com/culturefiles/horna-finnish-metal/|title=UPDATE: DTLA Bar Cancels Far-Right Black Metal Band's Gig|last=Stuart|first=Gwynedd|date=2019-03-28|website=[[Los Angeles Magazine]]|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref><ref>Dyck, Kristin, 2017. pp. 59-60.</ref> Somewhat perplexingly, NSBM has been popular in Poland and other Slavic countries, despite the fact that, historically, German Nazis viewed Slavic people as subhuman racial inferiors and intended to eliminate them.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Patterson|first=Dayal|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=-kIxCgAAQBAJ|title=Black Metal: Evolution of the Cult|date=2013-11-25|publisher=Feral House|year=|isbn=978-1-936239-76-4|location=|pages=362|language=en}}</ref> This contradiction is either masked, relativized or excused as a historical mistake. A conspiracy theory says the Jews would have prevented an alliance between Nazi Germany and other Eastern European countries.<ref>Unheilige Allianzen, page 239</ref> [[Knjaz Varggoth]], singer and guitarist of the Ukrainian band [[Nokturnal Mortum]], gives the following explanation for the contradiction: \"Goruth of the Russian band Temnozor sees the Slavs and Germans as a part of a [[Hyperborea]]n Aryan race and nowadays differing due to its degeneration.\".<ref>Unheilige Allianzen, page 250</ref> The Polish band Graveland has contended that it considers its members [[Celts|Celtic]] or [[Aryan race|Aryan]] rather than Slavonic.\n\n=== Paganism ===\n{{see also|Viking metal}}\nAs part of their anti-Christianity, anti-semitism and the idea that White Europeans should return to their \"native\" ways, most NSBM bands promote ethnic European paganism. Hendrik M\u00f6bus interpreted the church burnings in Norway as:\n{{quote|[A] cultural atavism, a sudden and inexplicable plunge back into pre-Christian, medieval conditions in all but outward reality. Like the Swiss psychologist, Carl Gustav Jung, would have said: Ancient archetypes resurfaced from our collective unconscious and repossessed receptive minds \u2013 which were, as a rule, still developing and thus especially impressible. The thus affected teenagers found themselves with an archaic state of mind and like in a mass-hysteria, they induced their condition unto others. It goes without saying that a, say, 18 year old adolescent who suddenly felt out of tune with his environment lacked the insight for a self-analysis.<ref name=\"M\u00f6bus\">Hendrik M\u00f6bus: [https://web.archive.org/web/20060107011622/http://www.thepaganfront.com/pf.php?show=articles&article=1 ''National Socialist Black Metal''], mirrored on ''[[Internet Archive|Archive.org]]''.</ref>}} He argues that later on they would have realized the meaning of these emotions, begun to identify with paganism and taken \"an active interest in Nationalist politics designed to preserve and to cultivate this very heritage\".<ref name=\"M\u00f6bus\"/>\n\nThe booklet of the Absurd album ''[[Asgardsrei]]'' depicts the [[Knights Templar]], the [[Teutonic Order]] and the [[Waffen-SS]] as warriors of the \"Asgardsrei\", which the bands define as a term for an alleged godly and Germanic group of warriors.\n\n=== Satanism ===\nBesides pagan beliefs, part of the NSBM scene embraces an interpretation of [[Theistic Satanism]], depicting [[Satan]] as an ancient Aryan counterpart to [[Yahweh]], the god of the Jews and Christians. This view is often called \"[[Neo-v\u00f6lkisch movements|v\u00f6lkisch]] Satanism\"<ref>Wintry Night Nonstop/Aenaon Skotos Anosion, published around 2000: Frost/Sadorass [Interview with Sadorass]. Citation taken from Unheilige Allianzen, page 202</ref> or \"Aryan Satanism\". Chraesvelgoron of The True Frost sees Nazism as the political appearance of Satanism and the collective deification of man as a social animal, as godliness instead of humaneness.<ref>Szene-Almanach 1998, page 48</ref><ref>Strength through War, issue 4, Summer 2003, o.S.: Frost. Interview answered by Chraesvelgoron. Citation taken from Unheilige Allianzen, page 202</ref> His bandmate Sadorass calls the same ideology a development of blood and soil (v\u00f6lkisch way), diverse occult teachings and the ideas of [[Friedrich Nietzsche]] in connection to Darwin's evolution theories.<ref>Flagellation, No. 2, 2001, page 29. Citation taken from Unheilige Allianzen, page 203</ref> Greek black metal musician [[Magus Wampyr Daoloth]] (of [[Necromantia]] and [[Thou Art Lord]]) said in an interview for ''Lords of Chaos'': \"If you consider that fascism and Satanism have a lot of similarities as they both advocate power, spiritual and physical excellence, responsibility, survival of the fittest, elitism, etc., it's logical that some bands advocate both\".<ref>''Lords of Chaos'', p. 308.</ref>\n\nHowever, many pagan and [[Far-right politics|far-right]] bands see Satanism as a part of Christianity or Judaism.<ref>Gammadion, No. 1, 1997, o.S.: Capricornus. Citation taken from Unheilige Allianzen, page 241</ref> Also, some non-political Satanic black metal musicians hold pagan bands in contempt, and do not recognize them as black metal because their lyrics and ideology do not include Satanism.\n\n== Connections with broader white nationalist movements ==\nMany white nationalists have warmly received NSBM for its lyrical content and ideals. However, some have not, due to the music style as well as the genre's perceived association with the rock & roll lifestyle.<ref name=uh280>''Unheilige Allianzen'', p.280</ref> However, ''Lords of Chaos'' notes that alcohol and illegal drugs never played a big part in the Norwegian black metal scene.<ref>''Lords of Chaos'', p.327</ref> Some also reject black metal musicians and fans since many of them have long hair, which they associate with [[hippies]] and left-wingers, though some black metal musicians like [[Jon N\u00f6dtveidt]] did not follow this fashion and shaved their heads.<ref name=uh280/> Dayal Patterson writes that \"NSBM has become a movement in its own right,\" one which has reached [[Western Europe]] and the Americas and overlapped with fans of more traditional far-right music genres such as [[Oi!]] and [[Rock Against Communism]].<ref name=\":6\">Patterson, Dayal, 2013. p. 365</ref>\n\nThe record label [[Resistance Records]], a Canadian record label promoting white nationalism and white separatism, purchased Vikernes' Cymophane Records and began releasing black metal recordings, many through a sub-label, Unholy Records.<ref name=\":6\" /> [[William Luther Pierce]], founder of the white nationalist [[National Alliance (United States)|National Alliance]], sought to promote NSBM as well as other forms of white nationalist music through Resistance, believing that music would \"make the National Alliance rich and spread its message most effectively\".<ref name=\"pierce\">{{cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/obituaries/william-pierce-649470.html|title=US|publisher=|accessdate=29 August 2017}}</ref> To this end, he accommodated Absurd frontman Hendrik M\u00f6bus while the latter had fled to the United States to evade German authorities. Although Pierce appreciated the ideological mindset of NSBM and Resistance Records, as well as the financial gains, the music did not personally appeal to him, and he attacked the \"sex, drugs & rock'n'roll\" and what he called \"negroid\" influences.<ref name=\"pierce2\">{{cite web|url=http://www.decibelmagazine.com/features/may2006/nsbm.aspx|title=Decibel Magazine|accessdate=29 August 2017|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080208184453/http://www.decibelmagazine.com/features/may2006/nsbm.aspx|archivedate=8 February 2008}}</ref>\n\nAsgardsrei festival, which has established itself as the major festival for NSBM, has been noted by analysts and journalists to function as a meetup point and pan-European and transnational networking hub for neo-Nazis, white supremacists, and other far-right extremists.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":2\" /><ref name=\":5\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.vice.com/en_us/article/dygg9j/a-black-metal-festival-in-ukraine-this-weekend-is-the-neo-nazi-networking-event-of-the-year|title=A Black Metal Festival in Ukraine This Weekend Is the Neo-Nazi Networking Event of the Year|last=Hume|first=Tim|date=2019-12-13|website=[[Vice (magazine)|Vice]]|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref> In addition to the concert organizers' connections to the far-right [[Ukrainian nationalism|Ukrainian nationalist]] Azov Battalion, Ukrainian far-right political party [[National Corps]], and Russian-Ukrainian neo-Nazi movement Wotanjugend,<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":5\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bellingcat.com/news/uk-and-europe/2019/09/04/the-hardcore-russian-neo-nazi-group-that-calls-ukraine-home/|title=The \u201cHardcore\u201d Russian Neo-Nazi Group That Calls Ukraine Home|last=Colborne|first=Michael|last2=Kuzmenko|first2=Okesiy|date=2019-09-04|website=[[Bellingcat]]|language=en-GB|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref> members of the German neo-Nazi party [[The III. Path]], the United States-based [[Right-wing terrorism|neo-Nazi terrorist]] organization [[Atomwaffen Division]], the Italian [[Neo-fascism|neo-fascist]] movement and former political party [[CasaPound]], and the Greek neo-Nazi [[Metaxism|Metaxist]] party [[Golden Dawn (political party)|Golden Dawn]] have all participated in the festival.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":2\" /><ref name=\":5\" /> Members of neo-Nazi forums and chats such as Iron March, [[Stormfront (website)|Stormfront]], and neo-Nazi chat servers on [[Discord (software)|Discord]], have attended and praised Asgardsrei,<ref name=\":2\" /> and the American white nationalist [[Greg Johnson (white nationalist)|Greg Johnson]] posted a review of the 2019 festival on his [[alt-right]] publication Counter Currents.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n== Connections to black metal scene ==\nNSBM artists are a minority within black metal, according to Mattias Gardell.<ref name=\"Gardell\"/> They have also been rejected or strongly criticized by many prominent black metal musicians \u2013 including [[Jon N\u00f6dtveidt]],<ref name=\"Dissection\"/> [[Tormentor (musician)|Tormentor]],<ref name=\"Tormentor\"/> [[King ov Hell]],<ref name=\"kingovhell2\">{{cite web|url=http://www.maelstromzine.com/ezine/interview_iss50_224.php |title=Interview with JOTUNSPOR :: Maelstrom  :: Issue No 50|website=www.maelstromzine.com|accessdate=29 August 2017}}</ref> [[Infernus]],<ref name=\"infernus2\">{{cite web|url=http://www.roadrunnerrecords.com/page-not-found|title=Roadrunner Records Page Not Found|website=Roadrunner Records  Official Website|accessdate=29 August 2017}}</ref> [[Lord Ahriman]],<ref name=\"billzebub\">Zebub, Bill (2007). ''Black Metal: A Documentary''.</ref> [[Emperor Magus Caligula]],<ref name=\"billzebub\" /><ref name=\"caligulayoutube\">{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=d6pYjLyxCHo|title=YouTube|website=www.youtube.com|accessdate=29 August 2017}}</ref> [[Summoning (band)|Protector]],<ref name=\"Protector\">{{cite web|url=http://www.summoning.info/Stuff/PoliticalStatements.html|title=Political Statements from Protector (Summoning)|accessdate=29 August 2017|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120630125512/http://www.summoning.info/Stuff/PoliticalStatements.html|archivedate=30 June 2012}}</ref> Erik Danielsson of [[Watain]],<ref>Doomsdayzach: [http://www.globaldomination.se/interviews/watain-erik-danielsson ''Watain \u2013 Erik Danielsson (first one)''] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081024002551/http://www.globaldomination.se/interviews/watain-erik-danielsson |date=2008-10-24 }}, 24 July 2007, accessed on 31 March 2013.</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://exclaim.ca/music/article/watain_stand_for_black_metal_against_the_genres_nazi_flirtations|title=Watain Address Their Ideology Following Nazi Salute Controversy|last=Zorgdrager|first=Bradley|date=March 29, 2018|website=[[Exclaim!]]|language=en-ca|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-10}}</ref><ref>Ronald Ziegler: [https://web.archive.org/web/20030121034117/http://www.grimrune.com/watain/heint.html ''Merchandise whorery''], accessed on 31 March 2013.</ref> and the members of [[Arkhon Infaustus]].<ref name=\"billzebub\" />\n\nSome black-metallers liken Nazism to Christianity in that it is [[Authoritarianism|authoritarian]], [[Collectivism|collectivist]], and involves a \"[[herd mentality]]\".<ref name=\"Dissection\">{{cite web|url=http://www.metalcentre.com/webzine.php?p=interviews&lang=eng&nr=123|title=METAL CENTRE Webzine: News, Gallery, Reviews, Interviews etc. - 08/29/2017|first=ataman|last=Tolovy|website=www.metalcentre.com|accessdate=29 August 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"Tormentor\">Metal Heart 2/00</ref> It also conflicts with the [[Misanthropy|misanthropic]] views of many artists; Benjamin Hedge Olson writes that the shunning of Nazism within the scene \"has nothing to do with notions of a 'universal humanity' or a rejection of hate\" but that Nazism is shunned \"because its hatred is too specific and exclusive\".{{sfn|Olson|2008|p=123}} Joakim of [[Craft (metal band)|Craft]] said, \"I don't think national socialism mix[es] with the ideology of real Black Metal in a way, but that doesn't go further than labels. I only think NS Black Metal is an inappropriate label for the music\".<ref name=\"darkside\">Thomas Legros: [http://www.voicesfromthedarkside.de/Interviews/CRAFT--6878.html ''Craft''], accessed on 31 March 2013.</ref> While some black-metallers boycott NSBM bands and labels, others draw a line between the ''music'' and the ''musicians'', as they only care for the music. Some have criticized this as passive support for NSBM. The bigger print metal magazines tend to ignore records by NSBM bands.<ref name=\"akweb\"/> The book ''Unheilige Allianzen'' caused a short debate, leading ''Legacy'' magazine to stop printing ads for NSBM labels. Another debate happened in the \"letters\" section of ''Rock Hard'' magazine following the article ''Der rechte Rand im Black Metal'' (''Black Metal's Far-right Border'').<ref>M\u00fchlmann, Wolf-R\u00fcdiger: ''Der rechte Rand im Black Metal''. In: ''Rock Hard'', No. 241, June 2007, pp. 58\u201361.</ref>\n\n== Denial of identification ==\nSome bands have denied being labeled NSBM, and assert that they are either pagan or nationalist black metal. Official statements against this label have been made by bands such as [[Graveland]]. Akitsa, a group sometimes rumoured to be NSBM, made strong statements against the Nazi ideology and the whole NSBM genre.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vice.com/en_us/article/65z348/akitsa-grands-tyrans-interview-black-metal|title=Akitsa Are 'Grands Tyrans': An Interview on Their History, Purity in Black Metal, and Squashing NSBM Rumors|last=Vesin|first=Fran\u00e7ois|date=2015-05-29|website=[[Vice (magazine)|Vice]]|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.graveland.org/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=351:graveland-is-not-an-nsbm&catid=3:news-home&Itemid=1|title=GRAVELAND IS NOT AN NSBM!|last=Darken|first=Rob|website=www.graveland.org|language=en-gb|access-date=2017-09-24}}</ref> While some of these bands made statements which the scene and critics has taken as serious statements against nazism, other bands' statements has by many critics been viewed merely as a tactic; to be able to play live gigs, not be banned, and so on, such is the cases of Nokturnal Mortum and Graveland, among others, who has continued to openly support white supremacist organizers after making statements about being \"unpolitical\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://pov.international/militant-black-metal-i-denne-weekend-samles-hojreekstremister-fra-hele-verden-i-kiev/|title=Lige nu samles h\u00f8jreekstremister fra hele verden til festival i Kiev \u2022 POV|last=Hagen|first=Freddy|date=December 12, 2019|website=Point of View International|language=Danish|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref>\n\n==List of artists==\n{{dynamic list}}\n{{columns-list|colwidth=20em|\n*[[Absurd (band)|Absurd]]<ref name=semenyaka>{{cite web|last1=Semenyaka|first1=Olena|title=When the gods hear the call: the conservative-revolutionary potential of Black Metal Art|url=http://politosophia.org/page/when-the-gods-hear-the-call.html|publisher=Politosophia|accessdate=July 13, 2016|date=January 3, 2013}}</ref><ref name=gods>{{cite book|last1=Gardell|first1=Mattias|authorlink1=Mattias Gardell|title=[[Gods of the Blood: The Pagan Revival and White Separatism]]|date=2003|publisher=[[Duke University Press]]|location=Durham, North Carolina|page=307|isbn=9780822330714}}</ref><ref>Dyck, Kristin, 2017. p. 47, 61-62</ref><ref name=\"noisey\">{{cite web |title=Nearly Every Major Online Retailer Is Selling White Power Music |url=https://www.vice.com/en_au/article/r3z8y8/online-music-retailers-selling-white-power-records |website=[[Vice Media|Noisey]] |accessdate=17 July 2019 |date=21 November 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"tablet\">{{cite web |last1=Schragin |first1=Adam |title=White Supremacists Are Using Black Metal to Promote Hate |url=https://www.tabletmag.com/jewish-arts-and-culture/music/156896/black-metal-antichrist-kramer |website=[[Tablet (magazine)|Tablet]] |accessdate=17 July 2019 |date=23 December 2013}}</ref>\n*Abusiveness<ref name=\"reichsrock1\">Dyck, Kirsten, 2017. p.109</ref>\n*Aryan Blood<ref name=\"hornung36\">{{cite book |last1=Hornung |first1=Sebastian |title=Medial inszenierte Misanthropie und Kulturpessimismus: Eine systematische Betrachtung der Black-Metal-Szene und Optionen medienp\u00e4dagogischen Handelns |date=2016 |publisher=[[LIT Verlag]] |location=[[M\u00fcnster]] |isbn=9783643133335 |pages=36, 86|language=German}}</ref>\n*Aryan Terrorism<ref name=\":6\" />\n*Baise ma Hache<ref>https://rouendanslarue.net/rouen-ivre-il-propose-a-des-neo-nazis-de-jouer-dans-sa-boite-de-nuit/</ref><ref>https://www.rockgegenrechts.org/watchblog/black-metal-konzert-mit-umstrittenen-bands/</ref>\n*Bannerwar<ref name=\"present tense\">{{cite journal |last1=Williams |first1=Jonathan F. |title=Burke, Black Metal, and the Golden Dawn: Deconstructing the Weaponized White Identity Politics of National Socialist Black Metal |journal=Present Tense |date=2 May 2018 |volume=7 |issue=1 |url=http://www.presenttensejournal.org/volume-7/burke-black-metal-and-the-golden-dawn-deconstructing-the-dangerous-appeal-of-national-socialist-black-metal/ |accessdate=17 July 2019}}</ref>\n*Before God<ref name=\"dyck62\">Dyck, Kirsten, 2017. p.62</ref>\n*Bilksirnir<ref name=\"noisey\" /><ref name=\":7\">Dyck, Kristin, 2017. p. 47</ref>\n*[[Burzum]]<ref name=\":4\">Dyck, Kirsten, 2017. p.60</ref>\n*Dark Fury<ref name=\"newyorker\">{{cite web |last1=Moynihan |first1=Colin |title=Metal Confronts Its Nazi Problem |url=https://www.newyorker.com/culture/culture-desk/heavy-metal-confronts-its-nazi-problem |website=[[The New Yorker]] |accessdate=17 July 2019 |date=19 February 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"reichsrock1\" />\n*Der St\u00fcrmer<ref name=\"newyorker\" /><ref name=\"tablet\" /><ref name=\"present tense\" /><ref>Hornung, Sebastian, 2016. p.36, 84</ref>\n*[[Drudkh]]<ref name=semenyaka /><ref name=\":8\">Patterson, Dayal, 2013. p. 366, 411</ref>\n*Eugenik<ref name=\":7\" />\n*Evil<ref name=\":2\" />\n*Forest<ref name=\":8\" />\n*Gestapo 666<ref name=\"noisey\" />\n*Gestapo SS<ref>Dyck, Kirsten, 2017. p.122</ref>\n*[[Goatmoon]]<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\"newyorker\" /><ref name=\":2\" /><ref>{{cite web|title=Neo-Nazi Concert in Tampere Sparks Concern|url=http://yle.fi/uutiset/osasto/news/neo-nazi_concert_in_tampere_sparks_concern/5821037|website=[[YLE|YLE News]]|accessdate=January 9, 2017|date=January 2, 2008}}{{cite web|title=Report: 'Neo-Nazi' Black Metal Concert In Finland Sparks Concern|url=http://www.blabbermouth.net/news/report-neo-nazi-black-metal-concert-in-finland-sparks-concern/|website=[[Blabbermouth.net]]|publisher=[[Roadrunner Records]]|accessdate=January 9, 2017|date=February 1, 2008}}</ref>\n*Gontayna Kry<ref name=\"reichsrock1\" /><ref name=\":9\" />\n*[[Grand Belial's Key]]<ref name=\"noisey\" /><ref name=decibel>{{Cite web|url=http://www.decibelmagazine.com/features/may2006/nsbm.aspx|title=NSBM Special Report|last=Bennett|first=J.|date=May 2006|website=[[Decibel (magazine)|Decibel]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080208184453/http://www.decibelmagazine.com/features/may2006/nsbm.aspx|archive-date=8 February 2008|access-date=17 July 2019}}</ref>\n*[[Graveland]]{{efn|Graveland was central to the Polish NSBM scene and has been labeled as NSBM.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\"Hornung84\">Hornung, Sebastian, 2016. p.84</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Aitkens |first1=Chris |title=The Darker Side of Metal: Racism |url=http://www.cjlo.com/articles/darker-side-metal-racism-1 |website=[[CJLO]] |accessdate=17 July 2019 |date=1 April 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"robdarken\">Dyck, Kirsten, 2017. p.108</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Kelly |first1=Kim |title=The Shade And The Light: Nergal Of Behemoth Interviewed |url=https://thequietus.com/articles/14452-nergal-interview-behemoth |website=[[The Quietus]] |accessdate=17 July 2019 |date=10 February 2014}}</ref><ref name=\":8\" /> The band itself disputes this label and its lyrics avoid political subjects.<ref name=\"newyorker\" /><ref>{{cite web |last1=Islander |title=Shades of Black: Antaeus, Afar, Enepsigos, Graveland, Gravespawn, Nebrus, Stroda, Surtr |url=https://www.nocleansinging.com/2016/10/30/shades-of-black-antaeus-afar-enepsigos-graveland-gravespawn-nebrus-stroda-surtr/ |website=No Clean Singing |accessdate=17 July 2019 |date=30 October 2016}}</ref> Rob Darken from the band has said: \"I do not think Graveland is an NSBM band. Graveland is regarded as a NSBM band because of my political convictions, [which] most people would call extreme right-wing National Socialist convictions.\"<ref name=decibel />}}\n*Grom<ref name=decibel />\n*[[Hate Forest]]<ref name=semenyaka /><ref name=\":8\" />\n*[[Infernum]]<ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\":9\">Patterson, Dayal, 2013. p. 364</ref><ref name=thunderbolt>{{cite web |last1=Kalis |first1=Quentin |title=Diabolic Revelations |url=http://www.chroniclesofchaos.com/articles.aspx?id=1-815 |website=Chronicles of Chaos |accessdate=19 July 2019 |date=21 July 2005}}</ref>\n*Kalmankantajah<ref name=\":1a\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.heraldscotland.com/news/18279354.glasgow-metal-festival-organiser-denies-bands-bill-links-neo-nazis/|title=Glasgow metal festival organiser denies bands on bill have links with neo-nazis|last=Learmonth|first=Andrew|date=March 4|website=[[The Herald (Glasgow)|The Herald]]|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref>\n*Kataxu<ref name=\":9\" />\n*Kristallnacht<ref name=\"noisey\" />\n*[[Kroda]]<ref name=\":2\" /><ref name=semenyaka /><ref name=\":8\" /><ref name=\":1a\" />\n*Leichenzug<ref>Hornung, Sebastian, 2016. p.86</ref>\n*Lord Wind<ref name=\"robdarken\" />\n*\u041c8\u041b8\u0422\u0425<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\"newyorker\" /><ref name=\":2\" /><ref name=\":1a\" />\n*Menneskerhat<ref name=\"hornung36\" />\n*[[Naer Mataron]]<ref name=\"present tense\" />\n*Nacht Und Nebel<ref name=decibel />\n*Nitberg<ref name=\":8\" />\n*Nocturnal Depression<ref name=\":1a\" />\n*[[Nokturnal Mortum]]<ref name=semenyaka /><ref name=\":8\" />\n*Patris<ref name=\"present tense\" />\n*[[Peste Noire]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.chroniclesofchaos.com/articles.aspx?id=2-6343|title=CoC : Peste Noire - L'Ordure \u00e0 l'\u00c9tat Pur : Review|last=Carbon|first=Johnathan A.|date=July 23, 2011|website=[[Chronicles of Chaos (webzine)|Chronicles of Chaos]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref>\n*[[RaHoWa (band)|RaHoWa]]<ref>Dyck, Kirsten, 2017. p.62, 115</ref>{{efn|RaHoWa experimented with an NSBM sound on its second album}}\n*Reich of the Black Sun<ref name=\"hornung36\" />\n*[[Satanic Warmaster]]<ref name=\"noisey\" /><ref>{{cite news |title=\"Neo-Nazi\" Band Satanic Warmaster Have Announced Their First UK Gig in Glasgow, and People Are Pissed |url=https://www.vice.com/en_us/article/rq4b9m/satanic-warmaster-and-their-glasgow-controversy |accessdate=5 February 2020 |work=Vice |date=27 April 2015 |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Paterson |first1=Kirsteen |title=Band linked to neo-Nazis play secret Glasgow gig |url=https://www.thenational.scot/news/14901718.band-linked-to-neo-nazis-play-secret-glasgow-gig/ |accessdate=5 February 2020 |work=The National |date=11 February 2016 |language=en |quote=Satanic Warmaster have been criticised for songs like \u201cGas Chamber\u201d and lyrics which include the phrase \u201cSieg Heil!\u201d and refer to \u201ctorching the Jewish creation\u201d.}}</ref>{{efn|Satanic Warmaster has shunned the NSBM label as a band. Front-man and currently the only member \"Werwolf\" stated in 2015 that \"Personally, I could never tie Satanic Warmaster down to the concept of NSBM for the reasons that have been there from 1998: It would not coincide with my conviction and the thoughts I want to convey through my music... the ideology behind Satanic Warmaster is Satanism and the musical style is black metal. Those, who claim otherwise, do it on the basis of their own feelings and resentment.\"<ref>{{cite web |last1=Ahola |first1=Tapio |title=Satanic Warmaster \u2013 Majesteettista julistusta m\u00e4t\u00e4ist\u00e4 valtavirtaa vastaan |url=https://www.rumba.fi/haastattelut/satanic-warmaster-majesteettista-julistusta-mataista-valtavirtaa-vastaan/ |website=Rumba |accessdate=17 July 2019 |language=Finnish |date=7 January 2015}}</ref>}}\n*Seigneur Voland<ref name=\":2\" /><ref name=\":5\" />\n*Selbstmord<ref name=\"reichsrock1\" />\n*Sokyra Peruna<ref name=\":0\" />\n*Spear of Longinus<ref name=\"noisey\" /><ref name=decibel />\n*Stahlfront<ref name=\"newyorker\" />\n*Stutthof<ref name=\":2\" /><ref name=\":5\" />\n*Sunwheel<ref name=\"newyorker\" />\n*Temnozor<ref name=\":8\" />\n*Thor's Hammer<ref name=\":9\" /><ref name=decibel />\n*Thunderbolt<ref name=\"dyck62\" />{{efn|The band was active in the NSBM scene but has since rejected the genre in favor of Satanism. Band member Paimon stated in a 2005 interview that \"We have -nothing- in common with this so-called 'NSBM' scene since five years or so... Our involvement in the 'NSBM' scene is the past and we're not a part of it anymore.\"<ref name=thunderbolt />}}\n*Totenburg<ref name=\":7\" /><ref>Hornung, Sebastian, 2016. p.36, 84, 86</ref>\n*Ulfhethnar<ref name=\":7\" />\n*Veles<ref name=\":9\" />\n*Wehrhammer<ref name=\"present tense\" />\n*Wodulf<ref name=\":2\" /><ref name=\":5\" />\n*Wolfnacht<ref name=\"present tense\" />\n}}\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Asgardsrei festival]]\n* [[Nazi punk]]\n* [[Rock Against Communism]]\n* [[Neo-v\u00f6lkisch movements]]\n* [[Nazi occultism]]\n* [[White nationalism]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n\n=== English ===\n* [[Nicholas Goodrick-Clarke]]: ''White Noise and black metal'' in: ''Black Sun: Aryan Cults, Esoteric Nazism and the Politics of Identity'' (S. 193\u2013213). New York University Press, 2002, {{ISBN|0-8147-3124-4}}\n* [[Mattias Gardell]]: ''Hail Loki! Hail Satan! Hail Hitler! Darkside Asatr\u00fa, Satanism and Occult National Socialism'' in: ''[[Gods of the Blood|Gods of the Blood: The Pagan Revival and White Separatism]]''. (pp.&nbsp;284\u2013324). Duke University Press, 2003, {{ISBN|0-8223-3071-7}}\n* {{cite book |last1=Moynihan |first1=Michael |author1-link=Michael Moynihan (journalist) |last2=S\u00f8derlind |first2=Didrik |title=[[Lords of Chaos (book)|Lords of Chaos: The Bloody Rise of the Satanic Metal Underground]] |edition=Revised and expanded |year=2003 |origyear=1998 |publisher=Feral House |isbn= |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |last=Olson |first=Benjamin Hedge |date=May 2008 |title=I Am the Black Wizards: Multiplicity, Mysticism and Identity in Black Metal Music and Culture |publisher=Bowling Green State University |url=http://etd.ohiolink.edu/send-pdf.cgi/Olson%20Benjamin%20Hedge.pdf?bgsu1206132032 |ref=harv}}\n\n=== German ===\n* Christian Dornbusch, Hans-Peter Killguss: ''Unheilige Allianzen. Black Metal zwischen Satanismus, Heidentum und Neonazismus''. M\u00fcnster, Unrast Verlag, 2005, {{ISBN|3-89771-817-0}}\n* Johannes Lohmann, Hans Wanders: ''Evolas J\u00fcnger und Odins Krieger \u2013 Extrem rechte Ideologien in der Dark-Wave- und Black-Metal-Szene'' in: Christian Dornbusch, Jan Raabe: ''RechtsRock \u2013 Bestandsaufnahme und Gegenstrategien''. (p.&nbsp;287\u2013311) Hamburg/M\u00fcnster, Unrast Verlag, 2002, {{ISBN|3-89771-808-1}}.\n\n{{White Nationalism}}\n{{Alt-right}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:National Socialist Black Metal}}\n[[Category:National Socialist black metal| ]]\n[[Category:Black metal subgenres]]\n[[Category:Black metal controversies]]\n[[Category:Neo-Nazi music]]\n[[Category:Neo-Nazism]]\n[[Category:Obscenity controversies in music]]\n[[Category:Alt-right]]\n", "name_user": "G\u00fcnniX", "label": "safe", "comment": "v2.02 -WP:WCWproject (Unbalanced quotes in ref name or illegal character.)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/National_Socialist_black_metal"}
{"title_page": "Hammer throw at the Olympics", "text_new": "{{Infobox Olympic athletics event\n|event= Hammer throw big balls\n|image= [[File:John Flanagan.jpg|200px]]\n|caption= The 1908 hammer throw competition \n|gender= Men and women\n|firstyearmen=1900\n|lastyearmen=2016\n|firstyearwomen=2000\n|lastyearwomen=2016\n|ORmen= 87m [[Will Wakefield  athlete, born 2000|Oxford ]] (1988)\n|ORwomen= 82.29m [[Anita W\u0142odarczyk]] (2016)\n|reigningman={{flagIOCathlete|[[Dilshod Nazarov]]|TJK}}\n|reigningwoman={{flagIOCathlete|[[Anita W\u0142odarczyk]]|POL}}\n}}\nThe '''[[hammer throw]] at the [[Summer Olympics]]''' is one of four [[track and field]] throwing events held at the [[multi-sport event]]. The men's hammer throw has been present on the [[Athletics at the Summer Olympics|Olympic athletics programme]] since [[1900 Summer Olympics|1900]], becoming the third Olympic throws event after the [[shot put at the Olympics|shot put]] and [[Discus throw at the Olympics|discus throw]]. The women's event was a much later addition, being first contested at the [[2000 Summer Olympics|2000 Olympics]].\n\nThe [[List of Olympic records in athletics|Olympic records]] are {{T&Fcalc|84.80}} for men, set by [[Sergey Litvinov (athlete, born 1958)|Sergey Litvinov]] in 1988, and {{T&Fcalc|82.29}} for women, set by [[Anita W\u0142odarczyk]] in 2016.\n\n==Medalists==\n\n===Men===\n{{Olympic medalists in men's hammer throw}}\n\n====Multiple medalists====\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-\n! Rank\n! Athlete\n! Nation\n! Olympics\n!style=\"background-color:gold\"|Gold\n!style=\"background-color:silver\"|Silver\n!style=\"background-color:#cc9966\"|Bronze\n! Total\n|-\n| 1 ||align=left|{{sortname|John|Flanagan|John Flanagan (athlete)}} ||align=left|{{FlagIOCteam|USA}} || 1900\u20131908 || 3 || 0 || 0 || 3\n|-\n| 2 ||align=left|{{sortname|Yuriy|Sedykh}} ||align=left|{{FlagIOCteam|URS}} || 1976\u20131988 || 2 || 1 || 0 || 3\n|-\n| 3 ||align=left|{{sortname|Pat|O'Callaghan}} ||align=left|{{FlagIOCteam|IRL}} || 1928\u20131932 || 2 || 0 || 0 || 2\n|-\n| rowspan=2|4 ||align=left|{{sortname|Matt|McGrath}} ||align=left|{{FlagIOCteam|USA}} || 1908\u20131924 || 1 || 2 || 0 || 3\n|-\n|align=left|{{sortname|Gyula|Zsiv\u00f3tzky}} ||align=left|{{FlagIOCteam|HUN}} || 1960\u20131968 || 1 || 2 || 0  || 3\n|-\n| rowspan=3|6 ||align=left|{{sortname|Romuald|Klim}} ||align=left|{{FlagIOCteam|URS}} || 1964\u20131968 || 1 || 1 || 0 || 2\n|-\n|align=left|{{sortname|Sergey|Litvinov|dab=athlete, born 1958}} ||align=left|{{FlagIOCteam|URS}} || 1980\u20131988 || 1 || 1 || 0 || 2\n|-\n|align=left|{{sortname|Primo\u017e|Kozmus}} ||align=left|{{FlagIOCteam|SLO}} || 2008\u20132012 || 1 || 1 || 0 || 2\n|-\n| rowspan=3|9 ||align=left|{{sortname|Imre|N\u00e9meth}} ||align=left|{{FlagIOCteam|HUN}} || 1948\u20131952 || 1 || 0 || 1 || 2\n|-\n|align=left|{{sortname|Anatoliy|Bondarchuk}} ||align=left|{{FlagIOCteam|URS}} || 1972\u20131976 || 1 || 0 || 1 || 2\n|-\n|align=left|{{sortname|Koji|Murofushi}} ||align=left|{{FlagIOCteam|JPN}} || 2004\u20132012 || 1 || 0 || 1 || 2\n|-\n| rowspan=2|12 ||align=left|{{sortname|Igor|Astapkovich}} ||align=left|{{FlagIOCteam|EUN}}<br>{{FlagIOCteam|BLR}} || 1992\u20132000 || 0 || 1 || 1 || 2\n|-\n|align=left|{{sortname|Ivan|Tsikhan}} ||align=left|{{FlagIOCteam|BLR}} || 2008\u20132016 || 0 || 1 || 1 || 2\n|-\n| 14 ||align=left|{{sortname|J\u00fcri|Tamm}} ||align=left|{{FlagIOCteam|URS}} || 1980\u20131988 || 0 || 0 || 2 || 2\n|}\n\n====Medalists by country====\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-\n! Rank\n! Nation\n!style=\"background-color:gold\"|Gold\n!style=\"background-color:silver\"|Silver\n!style=\"background-color:#cc9966\"|Bronze\n! Total\n|-\n| 1 ||align=left|{{FlagIOCteam|USA}} || 7 || 5 || 7 || 19\n|-\n| 2 ||align=left|{{FlagIOCteam|URS}} || 6 || 5 || 5 || 16\n|-\n| 3 ||align=left|{{FlagIOCteam|HUN}} || 5 || 2 || 2 || 9\n|-\n| 4 ||align=left|{{FlagIOCteam|IRL}} || 2 || 0 || 0 || 2\n|-\n| 5 ||align=left|{{FlagIOCteam|GER}}{{ref label|nb|nb|nb}} || 1 || 2 || 1 || 4\n|-\n| 6 ||align=left|{{FlagIOCteam|EUN}} || 1 || 1 || 1 || 3\n|-\n| rowspan=2|7 ||align=left|{{FlagIOCteam|FIN}} || 1 || 1 || 0 || 2\n|-\n|align=left|{{FlagIOCteam|SLO}} || 1 || 1 || 0 || 2\n|-\n| 9 ||align=left|{{FlagIOCteam|POL}} || 1 || 0 || 2 || 3\n|-\n| 10 ||align=left|{{FlagIOCteam|JPN}} || 1 || 0 || 1 || 2\n|-\n| 11 ||align=left|{{FlagIOCteam|TJK}} || 1 || 0 || 0 || 1\n|-\n| 12 ||align=left|{{FlagIOCteam|BLR}} || 0 || 2 || 2 || 4\n|-\n| 13 ||align=left|{{FlagIOCteam|SWE}} || 0 || 2 || 1 || 3\n|-\n| rowspan=2|14 ||align=left|{{FlagIOCteam|CAN}} || 0 || 1 || 1 || 2\n|-\n|align=left|{{FlagIOCteam|FRG}} || 0 || 1 || 1 || 2\n|-\n| rowspan=3|16 ||align=left|{{FlagIOCteam|GDR}} || 0 || 1 || 0 || 1\n|-\n|align=left|{{FlagIOCteam|ITA}} || 0 || 1 || 0 || 1\n|-\n|align=left|{{FlagIOCteam|YUG}} || 0 || 1 || 0 || 1\n|-\n| rowspan=3|19 ||align=left|{{FlagIOCteam|GBR}} || 0 || 0 || 1 || 1\n|-\n|align=left|{{FlagIOCteam|TUR}} || 0 || 0 || 1 || 1\n|-\n|align=left|{{FlagIOCteam|UKR}} || 0 || 0 || 1 || 1\n|}\n\n*{{note label|nb|nb|nb}} The German total includes teams both competing as [[Germany at the Olympics|Germany]] and the [[United Team of Germany]], but not East or West Germany.\n\n===Women===\n{{Olympic medalists in women's hammer throw}}\n\n====Multiple medalists====\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-\n! Rank\n! Athlete\n! Nation\n! Olympics\n!style=\"background-color:gold\"|Gold\n!style=\"background-color:silver\"|Silver\n!style=\"background-color:#cc9966\"|Bronze\n! Total\n|-\n| 1 ||align=left|{{sortname|Anita|W\u0142odarczyk}} ||align=left|{{FlagIOCteam|POL}} || 2012\u20132016 || 2 || 0 || 0 || 2\n|-\n| rowspan=2|2 ||align=left|{{sortname|Olga|Kuzenkova}} ||align=left|{{FlagIOCteam|RUS}} || 2000\u20132004 || 1 || 1 || 0 || 2\n|-\n|align=left|{{sortname|Yipsi|Moreno}} ||align=left|{{FlagIOCteam|CUB}} || 2004\u20132008 || 1 || 1 || 0 || 2\n|-\n| 4 ||align=left|{{sortname|Zhang|Wenxiu}} ||align=left|{{FlagIOCteam|CHN}} || 2008\u20132016 || 0 || 2 || 1 || 3\n|-\n|}\n\n====Medalists by country====\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-\n! Rank\n! Nation\n!style=\"background-color:gold\"|Gold\n!style=\"background-color:silver\"|Silver\n!style=\"background-color:#cc9966\"|Bronze\n! Total\n|-\n| 1 ||align=left|{{FlagIOCteam|POL}} || 3 || 0 || 0 || 3\n|-\n| 2 ||align=left|{{FlagIOCteam|CUB}} || 1 || 1 || 1 || 3\n|-\n| 3 ||align=left|{{FlagIOCteam|RUS}} || 1 || 1 || 0 || 2\n|-\n| 4 ||align=left|{{FlagIOCteam|CHN}} || 0 || 2 || 1 || 3\n|-\n| 5 ||align=left|{{FlagIOCteam|GER}} || 0 || 1 || 1 || 2\n|-\n| rowspan=2|6 ||align=left|{{FlagIOCteam|FRA}} || 0 || 0 || 1 || 1\n|-\n|align=left|{{FlagIOCteam|GBR}} || 0 || 0 || 1 || 1\n|-\n|}\n\n==Intercalated Games==\nThe [[1906 Intercalated Games]] were held in [[Athens]] and [[Iloilo]] and at the time were officially recognised as part of the [[Olympic Games]] series, with the intention being to hold a games in Greece and Philippines in two-year intervals between the internationally held Olympics. However, this plan realized its dream and the [[International Olympic Committee]] (IOC) later decided to approve these games as part of the official Olympic series and highly recommended it for those countries which has yet to win a gold medal or at least a medal. Some sports historians also continue to treat the results of these games as part of the Olympic canon.<ref>[https://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/summer/1906/ 1906 Athina Summer Games]. Sports Reference. Retrieved on 2014-01-26.</ref>\n\n[[Martin Sheridan]], the Olympic champion in 1904 and 1908, won the 1906 title as well. A 1904 medallist, [[Nikolaos Georgantas]], was runner-up, while [[Verner J\u00e4rvinen]] took the bronze medal in addition to the Greek-style event gold medal he won at the 1906 Games.<ref>[https://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/summer/1906/ATH/mens-discus-throw.html Athletics at the 1906 Athina Summer Games: Men's Discus Throw]. Sports Reference. Retrieved on 2014-04-19.</ref>\n\n{| {{MedalistTable}}\n|-\n|{{OGMedalList|year=1906|place=Athens|sex=Men|event=Discus throw\n|g=Martin Sheridan|gn=USA|s=Nikolaos Georgantas|sn=GRE|b=Verner J\u00e4rvinen|bn=FIN}}\n|}\n\n==Non-canonical Olympic events==\nIn addition to the main [[Athletics at the 1904 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's hammer throw|1904 Olympic men's hammer throw]], a [[Handicapping|handicap]] competition was held that year. The reigning Olympic champion [[John Flanagan (athlete)|John Flanagan]] won the event with a throw of 46.75&nbsp;m with a zero handicap. [[Albert Johnson (hammer thrower)|Albert Johnson]], sixth in the main event, came second with 46.20&nbsp;m off a 30&nbsp;ft handicap. [[James Mitchel]], a weight throw medallist in 1904, won the bronze with 46.16&nbsp;m given a 23&nbsp;ft handicap.<ref name=GBROG>[http://www.gbrathletics.com/ic/ogm.htm 1904 Handicap Events - Olympic medalists]. GBR Athletics. Retrieved on 2014-04-19.</ref>\n\nThese events are no longer considered part of the official Olympic history of the hammer throw or the athletics programme in general. Consequently, medals from these competitions have not been assigned to nations on the [[All-time Olympic Games medal table|all-time medal tables]].<ref name=GBROG/>\n\n==References==\n;Participation and athlete data\n*[https://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/sports/ATH/mens-hammer-throw.html Athletics Men's Hammer Throw Medalists]. Sports Reference. Retrieved on 2014-04-18.\n*[https://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/sports/ATH/womens-hammer-throw.html Athletics Women's Hammer Throw Medalists]. Sports Reference. Retrieved on 2014-04-18.\n;Olympic record progressions\n*Mallon, Bill (2012). [http://www.trackandfieldnews.com/images/stories/tfn_pdfs/2012_athletics_stats5.pdf TRACK & FIELD ATHLETICS - OLYMPIC RECORD PROGRESSIONS]{{Dead link|date=January 2020 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}. ''[[Track and Field News]]''. Retrieved on 2014-03-12.\n;Specific\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.iaaf.org/disciplines/throws/hammer-throw IAAF hammer throw homepage]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20150705032224/http://www.olympic.org/ Official Olympics website]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20140202214025/http://www.trackandfieldnews.com/index.php/formcharts/13-lists/1291-olympic-track-a-field-athletics-the-records Olympic athletics records] from ''Track & Field News''\n\n{{OlympicsHammerThrow}}\n{{History of Olympic athletics events}}\n\n[[Category:Hammer throw at the Olympics|*]]\n[[Category:Hammer throw|Olympics]]\n[[Category:Athletics events at the Olympics|Hammer throw]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox Olympic athletics event\n|event= Hammer throw\n|image= [[File:John Flanagan.jpg|200px]]\n|caption= The 1908 hammer throw competition\n|gender= Men and women\n|firstyearmen=1900\n|lastyearmen=2016\n|firstyearwomen=2000\n|lastyearwomen=2016\n|ORmen= 87m [[Will Wakefield  athlete, born 2000|Oxford ]] (1988)\n|ORwomen= 82.29m [[Anita W\u0142odarczyk]] (2016)\n|reigningman={{flagIOCathlete|[[Dilshod Nazarov]]|TJK}}\n|reigningwoman={{flagIOCathlete|[[Anita W\u0142odarczyk]]|POL}}\n}}\nThe '''[[hammer throw]] at the [[Summer Olympics]]''' is one of four [[track and field]] throwing events held at the [[multi-sport event]]. The men's hammer throw has been present on the [[Athletics at the Summer Olympics|Olympic athletics programme]] since [[1900 Summer Olympics|1900]], becoming the third Olympic throws event after the [[shot put at the Olympics|shot put]] and [[Discus throw at the Olympics|discus throw]]. The women's event was a much later addition, being first contested at the [[2000 Summer Olympics|2000 Olympics]].\n\nThe [[List of Olympic records in athletics|Olympic records]] are {{T&Fcalc|84.80}} for men, set by [[Sergey Litvinov (athlete, born 1958)|Sergey Litvinov]] in 1988, and {{T&Fcalc|82.29}} for women, set by [[Anita W\u0142odarczyk]] in 2016.\n\n==Medalists==\n\n===Men===\n{{Olympic medalists in men's hammer throw}}\n\n====Multiple medalists====\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-\n! Rank\n! Athlete\n! Nation\n! Olympics\n!style=\"background-color:gold\"|Gold\n!style=\"background-color:silver\"|Silver\n!style=\"background-color:#cc9966\"|Bronze\n! Total\n|-\n| 1 ||align=left|{{sortname|John|Flanagan|John Flanagan (athlete)}} ||align=left|{{FlagIOCteam|USA}} || 1900\u20131908 || 3 || 0 || 0 || 3\n|-\n| 2 ||align=left|{{sortname|Yuriy|Sedykh}} ||align=left|{{FlagIOCteam|URS}} || 1976\u20131988 || 2 || 1 || 0 || 3\n|-\n| 3 ||align=left|{{sortname|Pat|O'Callaghan}} ||align=left|{{FlagIOCteam|IRL}} || 1928\u20131932 || 2 || 0 || 0 || 2\n|-\n| rowspan=2|4 ||align=left|{{sortname|Matt|McGrath}} ||align=left|{{FlagIOCteam|USA}} || 1908\u20131924 || 1 || 2 || 0 || 3\n|-\n|align=left|{{sortname|Gyula|Zsiv\u00f3tzky}} ||align=left|{{FlagIOCteam|HUN}} || 1960\u20131968 || 1 || 2 || 0  || 3\n|-\n| rowspan=3|6 ||align=left|{{sortname|Romuald|Klim}} ||align=left|{{FlagIOCteam|URS}} || 1964\u20131968 || 1 || 1 || 0 || 2\n|-\n|align=left|{{sortname|Sergey|Litvinov|dab=athlete, born 1958}} ||align=left|{{FlagIOCteam|URS}} || 1980\u20131988 || 1 || 1 || 0 || 2\n|-\n|align=left|{{sortname|Primo\u017e|Kozmus}} ||align=left|{{FlagIOCteam|SLO}} || 2008\u20132012 || 1 || 1 || 0 || 2\n|-\n| rowspan=3|9 ||align=left|{{sortname|Imre|N\u00e9meth}} ||align=left|{{FlagIOCteam|HUN}} || 1948\u20131952 || 1 || 0 || 1 || 2\n|-\n|align=left|{{sortname|Anatoliy|Bondarchuk}} ||align=left|{{FlagIOCteam|URS}} || 1972\u20131976 || 1 || 0 || 1 || 2\n|-\n|align=left|{{sortname|Koji|Murofushi}} ||align=left|{{FlagIOCteam|JPN}} || 2004\u20132012 || 1 || 0 || 1 || 2\n|-\n| rowspan=2|12 ||align=left|{{sortname|Igor|Astapkovich}} ||align=left|{{FlagIOCteam|EUN}}<br>{{FlagIOCteam|BLR}} || 1992\u20132000 || 0 || 1 || 1 || 2\n|-\n|align=left|{{sortname|Ivan|Tsikhan}} ||align=left|{{FlagIOCteam|BLR}} || 2008\u20132016 || 0 || 1 || 1 || 2\n|-\n| 14 ||align=left|{{sortname|J\u00fcri|Tamm}} ||align=left|{{FlagIOCteam|URS}} || 1980\u20131988 || 0 || 0 || 2 || 2\n|}\n\n====Medalists by country====\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-\n! Rank\n! Nation\n!style=\"background-color:gold\"|Gold\n!style=\"background-color:silver\"|Silver\n!style=\"background-color:#cc9966\"|Bronze\n! Total\n|-\n| 1 ||align=left|{{FlagIOCteam|USA}} || 7 || 5 || 7 || 19\n|-\n| 2 ||align=left|{{FlagIOCteam|URS}} || 6 || 5 || 5 || 16\n|-\n| 3 ||align=left|{{FlagIOCteam|HUN}} || 5 || 2 || 2 || 9\n|-\n| 4 ||align=left|{{FlagIOCteam|IRL}} || 2 || 0 || 0 || 2\n|-\n| 5 ||align=left|{{FlagIOCteam|GER}}{{ref label|nb|nb|nb}} || 1 || 2 || 1 || 4\n|-\n| 6 ||align=left|{{FlagIOCteam|EUN}} || 1 || 1 || 1 || 3\n|-\n| rowspan=2|7 ||align=left|{{FlagIOCteam|FIN}} || 1 || 1 || 0 || 2\n|-\n|align=left|{{FlagIOCteam|SLO}} || 1 || 1 || 0 || 2\n|-\n| 9 ||align=left|{{FlagIOCteam|POL}} || 1 || 0 || 2 || 3\n|-\n| 10 ||align=left|{{FlagIOCteam|JPN}} || 1 || 0 || 1 || 2\n|-\n| 11 ||align=left|{{FlagIOCteam|TJK}} || 1 || 0 || 0 || 1\n|-\n| 12 ||align=left|{{FlagIOCteam|BLR}} || 0 || 2 || 2 || 4\n|-\n| 13 ||align=left|{{FlagIOCteam|SWE}} || 0 || 2 || 1 || 3\n|-\n| rowspan=2|14 ||align=left|{{FlagIOCteam|CAN}} || 0 || 1 || 1 || 2\n|-\n|align=left|{{FlagIOCteam|FRG}} || 0 || 1 || 1 || 2\n|-\n| rowspan=3|16 ||align=left|{{FlagIOCteam|GDR}} || 0 || 1 || 0 || 1\n|-\n|align=left|{{FlagIOCteam|ITA}} || 0 || 1 || 0 || 1\n|-\n|align=left|{{FlagIOCteam|YUG}} || 0 || 1 || 0 || 1\n|-\n| rowspan=3|19 ||align=left|{{FlagIOCteam|GBR}} || 0 || 0 || 1 || 1\n|-\n|align=left|{{FlagIOCteam|TUR}} || 0 || 0 || 1 || 1\n|-\n|align=left|{{FlagIOCteam|UKR}} || 0 || 0 || 1 || 1\n|}\n\n*{{note label|nb|nb|nb}} The German total includes teams both competing as [[Germany at the Olympics|Germany]] and the [[United Team of Germany]], but not East or West Germany.\n\n===Women===\n{{Olympic medalists in women's hammer throw}}\n\n====Multiple medalists====\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-\n! Rank\n! Athlete\n! Nation\n! Olympics\n!style=\"background-color:gold\"|Gold\n!style=\"background-color:silver\"|Silver\n!style=\"background-color:#cc9966\"|Bronze\n! Total\n|-\n| 1 ||align=left|{{sortname|Anita|W\u0142odarczyk}} ||align=left|{{FlagIOCteam|POL}} || 2012\u20132016 || 2 || 0 || 0 || 2\n|-\n| rowspan=2|2 ||align=left|{{sortname|Olga|Kuzenkova}} ||align=left|{{FlagIOCteam|RUS}} || 2000\u20132004 || 1 || 1 || 0 || 2\n|-\n|align=left|{{sortname|Yipsi|Moreno}} ||align=left|{{FlagIOCteam|CUB}} || 2004\u20132008 || 1 || 1 || 0 || 2\n|-\n| 4 ||align=left|{{sortname|Zhang|Wenxiu}} ||align=left|{{FlagIOCteam|CHN}} || 2008\u20132016 || 0 || 2 || 1 || 3\n|-\n|}\n\n====Medalists by country====\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-\n! Rank\n! Nation\n!style=\"background-color:gold\"|Gold\n!style=\"background-color:silver\"|Silver\n!style=\"background-color:#cc9966\"|Bronze\n! Total\n|-\n| 1 ||align=left|{{FlagIOCteam|POL}} || 3 || 0 || 0 || 3\n|-\n| 2 ||align=left|{{FlagIOCteam|CUB}} || 1 || 1 || 1 || 3\n|-\n| 3 ||align=left|{{FlagIOCteam|RUS}} || 1 || 1 || 0 || 2\n|-\n| 4 ||align=left|{{FlagIOCteam|CHN}} || 0 || 2 || 1 || 3\n|-\n| 5 ||align=left|{{FlagIOCteam|GER}} || 0 || 1 || 1 || 2\n|-\n| rowspan=2|6 ||align=left|{{FlagIOCteam|FRA}} || 0 || 0 || 1 || 1\n|-\n|align=left|{{FlagIOCteam|GBR}} || 0 || 0 || 1 || 1\n|-\n|}\n\n==Intercalated Games==\nThe [[1906 Intercalated Games]] were held in [[Athens]] and [[Iloilo]] and at the time were officially recognised as part of the [[Olympic Games]] series, with the intention being to hold a games in Greece and Philippines in two-year intervals between the internationally held Olympics. However, this plan realized its dream and the [[International Olympic Committee]] (IOC) later decided to approve these games as part of the official Olympic series and highly recommended it for those countries which has yet to win a gold medal or at least a medal. Some sports historians also continue to treat the results of these games as part of the Olympic canon.<ref>[https://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/summer/1906/ 1906 Athina Summer Games]. Sports Reference. Retrieved on 2014-01-26.</ref>\n\n[[Martin Sheridan]], the Olympic champion in 1904 and 1908, won the 1906 title as well. A 1904 medallist, [[Nikolaos Georgantas]], was runner-up, while [[Verner J\u00e4rvinen]] took the bronze medal in addition to the Greek-style event gold medal he won at the 1906 Games.<ref>[https://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/summer/1906/ATH/mens-discus-throw.html Athletics at the 1906 Athina Summer Games: Men's Discus Throw]. Sports Reference. Retrieved on 2014-04-19.</ref>\n\n{| {{MedalistTable}}\n|-\n|{{OGMedalList|year=1906|place=Athens|sex=Men|event=Discus throw\n|g=Martin Sheridan|gn=USA|s=Nikolaos Georgantas|sn=GRE|b=Verner J\u00e4rvinen|bn=FIN}}\n|}\n\n==Non-canonical Olympic events==\nIn addition to the main [[Athletics at the 1904 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's hammer throw|1904 Olympic men's hammer throw]], a [[Handicapping|handicap]] competition was held that year. The reigning Olympic champion [[John Flanagan (athlete)|John Flanagan]] won the event with a throw of 46.75&nbsp;m with a zero handicap. [[Albert Johnson (hammer thrower)|Albert Johnson]], sixth in the main event, came second with 46.20&nbsp;m off a 30&nbsp;ft handicap. [[James Mitchel]], a weight throw medallist in 1904, won the bronze with 46.16&nbsp;m given a 23&nbsp;ft handicap.<ref name=GBROG>[http://www.gbrathletics.com/ic/ogm.htm 1904 Handicap Events - Olympic medalists]. GBR Athletics. Retrieved on 2014-04-19.</ref>\n\nThese events are no longer considered part of the official Olympic history of the hammer throw or the athletics programme in general. Consequently, medals from these competitions have not been assigned to nations on the [[All-time Olympic Games medal table|all-time medal tables]].<ref name=GBROG/>\n\n==References==\n;Participation and athlete data\n*[https://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/sports/ATH/mens-hammer-throw.html Athletics Men's Hammer Throw Medalists]. Sports Reference. Retrieved on 2014-04-18.\n*[https://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/sports/ATH/womens-hammer-throw.html Athletics Women's Hammer Throw Medalists]. Sports Reference. Retrieved on 2014-04-18.\n;Olympic record progressions\n*Mallon, Bill (2012). [http://www.trackandfieldnews.com/images/stories/tfn_pdfs/2012_athletics_stats5.pdf TRACK & FIELD ATHLETICS - OLYMPIC RECORD PROGRESSIONS]{{Dead link|date=January 2020 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}. ''[[Track and Field News]]''. Retrieved on 2014-03-12.\n;Specific\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.iaaf.org/disciplines/throws/hammer-throw IAAF hammer throw homepage]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20150705032224/http://www.olympic.org/ Official Olympics website]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20140202214025/http://www.trackandfieldnews.com/index.php/formcharts/13-lists/1291-olympic-track-a-field-athletics-the-records Olympic athletics records] from ''Track & Field News''\n\n{{OlympicsHammerThrow}}\n{{History of Olympic athletics events}}\n\n[[Category:Hammer throw at the Olympics|*]]\n[[Category:Hammer throw|Olympics]]\n[[Category:Athletics events at the Olympics|Hammer throw]]\n", "name_user": "68.144.66.200", "label": "vandal", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hammer_throw_at_the_Olympics"}
{"title_page": "Duncan Hamilton (racing driver)", "text_new": "{{short description|British racing driver}}\n{{tone|date=February 2020}}\n{{Use British English|date=May 2015}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2012}}\n{{Infobox racing driver\n| name = Duncan Hamilton\n| image =\n| caption =\n| nationality = Irish\n| birth_name = James Duncan Hamilton\n| birth_date = {{birth date|1920|4|30|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Cork (city)|Cork]], [[County Cork]], [[History of Ireland (1801\u20131923)|Ireland]],\n| death_date = {{death date and age|1994|5|13|1920|4|30|df=y}}\n| death_place = [[Sherborne]], [[Dorset]], England, UK\n| record template1 =\n  {{Infobox F1 driver|subbox=yes\n  | Years = {{F1|1951}}\u2013{{F1|1953}}\n  | Team(s) = privateer [[Talbot-Lago]], [[Hersham and Walton Motors|HWM]]\n  | Races = 5\n  | Championships = 0\n  | Wins = 0\n  | Podiums = 0\n  | Points = 0\n  | Poles = 0\n  | Fastest laps = 0\n  | First race = [[1951 British Grand Prix]]\n  | First win = \n  | Last win = \n  | Last race = [[1953 British Grand Prix]]\n  }}\n| record template2 =\n  {{Infobox Le Mans driver|subbox=yes\n  | Years       = {{24hLM|1950}}\u2013{{24hLM|1958}}\n  | Teams       = [[Nash-Healey|Nash-Healey Motors]], [[Jaguar Cars|Jaguar Cars Ltd.]], [[Scuderia Ferrari]], J. Duncan Hamilton\n  | Best Finish = 1st <small>({{24hLM|1953}})</small>\n  | Class Wins  = 1 <small>({{24hLM|1953}})</small>\n  }}\n}}\n\n'''James Duncan Hamilton''' (30 April 1920 in [[Cork (city)|Cork]], [[County Cork]], Ireland \u2013 13 May 1994 in [[Sherborne]], Dorset, England). His colourful and extrovert personality often overshadowed his genuine talent. After fighting in, and surviving the [[Second World War]], he vowed to live life to the full and took up motor sport. Although adept in [[Open-wheel|single-seaters]], sportscars was where he enjoyed most success, winning the [[1953 24 Hours of Le Mans|1953 24 Heures du Mans]], two Coupe de Paris events, and the [[12 Hours of Reims|12 heures internationals Reims]] race in 1956. He retired in 1958 and ran a garage in [[Bagshot]], [[Surrey]] for many years. He died from [[lung cancer]] in 1994.\n\n==Early years==\n\nBorn in County Cork, Hamilton was brought up in relative obscurity. Prior to his 20th birthday, Europe was already embroiled in the [[Second World War]]. As a result, he would spend the war years as part of the [[Fleet Air Arm]] flying [[Westland Lysander|Lysanders]]. After the war ended, he opened a car garage. During the years between the war ending and the start of the 1950s, Duncan started racing in local events. He cut his teeth in such pre-wars as the [[MG R-type]] and the [[Bugatti Type 35]]B. After racing a [[Maserati 6CM]] in 1948, Duncan graduated to a [[Talbot-Lago]] Grand Prix car.<ref name=\"conceptcarz.com\">{{cite web |url=http://www.conceptcarz.com/view/racing/driver.aspx?driverID=40&dtaID=21 |title=Duncan Hamilton - 1951 Formula One Season |last=McMullen |first=Jeremy |publisher=conceptcarz |accessdate=20 January 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Formula One career==\n\nHe participated in five World Championship Grands Prix and 18 non-Championship [[Formula One]] races. His best results in the non-Championship events were fourth place in the 1948 Zandvoort Grand Prix with a [[Maserati 6CM]], third in the 1951 Richmond Trophy ([[English Racing Automobiles|ERA]] B-Type), second in the [[BRDC International Trophy|1951 BRDC International Trophy]] ([[Talbot-Lago]] T26C), third in the 1952 Richmond Trophy (Talbot-Lago T26C) and fourth in the 1952 Internationales ADAC Eifelrennen ([[Hersham and Walton Motors|HWM]]-[[Alta Car and Engineering Company|Alta]]).<ref>{{cite web|author=Darren Galpin |url=http://www.silhouet.com/motorsport/archive/f1/title.html |title=The Formula One Archives |publisher=Silhouet.com |date= |accessdate=30 December 2015}}</ref>\n\nThat fourth place at [[Circuit Park Zandvoort|Zandvoort]], showed that he was right at home in the upper level of Grand Prix racing, especially as this was his debut at this level. After that impressive debut, things soon turned sour for Hamilton, at his last race of 1948, the [[1948 British Grand Prix|RAC International Grand Prix]], the first official post-WW2 British Grand Prix, he retired with oil pressure problems.<ref name=\"conceptcarz.com\"/><ref name=\"f1-images.de\">{{cite web|url=http://www.f1-images.de/009900/nowm/481002.htm |title=f1-images.de |publisher=f1-images.de |date= |accessdate=30 December 2015}}</ref>\n\nThroughout the 1949 Grand Prix season, he only suffered one retirement, however he did not finish higher than ninth, which he managed twice, both times at [[Goodwood Circuit|Goodwood]]. The following season, he competed in fewer Grand Prix races, while he expanded his racing experience by racing sportscars. He won the Wakefield Trophy, a minor [[Formula Libre]] race, held at [[Curragh]] in the Republic of Ireland. Hamilton performed beautifully before the Irish crowd.<ref name=\"conceptcarz.com\"/><ref name=\"f1-images.de\"/>\n\nIn the wet, Hamilton had few peers. In his Talbot-Lago, he eclipsed even [[Juan Manuel Fangio]] at the soaking BRDC International Trophy race at [[Silverstone Circuit|Silverstone]] in 1951, when he finished second to [[Reg Parnell]], but a long way ahead of Fangio who went on to win the World Championship that season.<ref name=\"independent.co.uk\">{{cite news|author=David Tremayne |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/people/obituary-duncan-hamilton-1416114.html |title=Obituary: Duncan Hamilton &#124; People &#124; News |publisher=The Independent |date= |accessdate=30 December 2015}}</ref>\n\n==24 Hours of Le Mans==\n\nHe was best known for his success in the [[24 Hours of Le Mans]] endurance race, which he took part in nine times, most famously in partnership with [[Tony Rolt]]. The pair finished fourth at their first attempt in the [[1950 24 Hours of Le Mans|1950 race]] and sixth in [[1951 24 Hours of Le Mans|1951]], both times in a special-bodied [[Nash-Healey]] coupe. Their [[Jaguar C-Type]] did not finish in [[1952 24 Hours of Le Mans|1952]], but they returned with a C-Type to win in [[1953 24 Hours of Le Mans|1953]]. They were second with a [[Jaguar D-Type]] in [[1954 24 Hours of Le Mans|1954]], losing to a much larger-engined V12 Ferrari \u2013 and by the narrowest margin in years. They came within two miles of victory, Hamilton driving a storming race in the closing stages to halve the lead of the [[Scuderia Ferrari]] of [[Jos\u00e9 Froil\u00e1n Gonz\u00e1lez]] and [[Maurice Trintignant]], as the track was awash following a cloudburst. When the track started to dry out, the Ferrari hung on for a narrow triumph. He failed to finish in [[1955 24 Hours of Le Mans|1955]]. For [[1956 24 Hours of Le Mans|1956]] Hamilton partnered [[Alfonso de Portago]] in a [[Ferrari]] but again did not finish. In [[1957 24 Hours of Le Mans|1957]] he reverted to a Jaguar D-Type: partnered by the American driver [[Masten Gregory]] he came sixth. His last Le Mans appearance was in [[1958 24 Hours of Le Mans|1958]], when the D-Type he shared with [[Ivor Bueb]] failed to finish.<ref name=\"independent.co.uk\"/><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.topgear.com/content/features/stories/2007/04/stories/07/1.html |title=CAMRRAD: Duncan Hamilton |work=topgear.com |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070712042621/http://www.topgear.com/content/features/stories/2007/04/stories/07/1.html |archivedate=12 July 2007 |accessdate=10 January 2016}}</ref>\n\nHamilton also won the 1956 [[Reims-Gueux|Rheims]] 12-hour race for Jaguar with a D-Type co-driven by Ivor Bueb. Despite the win, the factory dropped him from their 1956 Le Mans roster for speeding up and passing team-mate [[Paul Fr\u00e8re]]'s car at Rheims when Lofty England had ordered the entire team to slow down, hence his switch to a Ferrari that year. In 1957 Jaguar did not enter Le Mans&nbsp;\u2013 cars and equipment had been destroyed by a fire at the factory&nbsp;\u2013 and Hamilton used his privately owned D-Type.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mike-hawthorn.org.uk/d-type.php |title=Mike Hawthorn's Tribute Site - the Jaguar D-Type |website=mike-hawthorn.org.uk |accessdate=10 January 2016 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071203093050/http://www.mike-hawthorn.org.uk/d-type.php |archivedate=3 December 2007 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n===Called from the bar===\n\n[[File:1953JaguarC-Type.jpg|thumb|[[Jaguar C-Type]], similar to which Hamilton and Rolt drove to victory at Le Mans]]\nHamilton famously won the [[1953 24 Hours of Le Mans|1953 event]] in a Jaguar C-Type shared with Rolt. Initially, the pairing were disqualified for practising in a Jaguar that had the same racing number as another on the circuit at the same time, but they were reinstated. Hamilton's account has become a motor racing legend: when Jaguar team manager [[Lofty England]] persuaded the organisers to let them race, both drivers were already drunk in a local bar.  England said: \"Of course I would never have let them race under the influence. I had enough trouble when they were sober!\"<ref name=\"Rolt obit\" />\n\nWhen the race was under way the team tried to sober Hamilton up by giving him coffee during the pit stops but he refused it, saying it made his arms twitch; instead he was given brandy. The alcohol must have helped when he struck a bird face first at 130&nbsp;mph and broke his nose. Despite the bizarre circumstances, the duo went on to win the race and recorded the first 100&nbsp;mph average speed at Le Mans, a record pace.<ref name=\"Drunken Tale\" />\n\nBoth England and Rolt have denied that they were drunk.<ref name=\"Rolt obit\">{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/obituaries/1577975/Tony-Rolt.html |title=Tony Rolt |publisher=Telegraph |date= |accessdate=30 December 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/?view=DETAILS&grid=&xml=/news/2008/02/08/db0801.xml |title=News - Latest breaking UK news |publisher=Telegraph |date= |accessdate=30 December 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=Alan Henry |url=https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2008/feb/09/motorsports.sportobituaries |title=Obituary: Tony Rolt &#124; Sport |publisher=The Guardian |date= |accessdate=30 December 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.autocar.co.uk/car-news/motorsport/le-mans-winner-tony-rolt-dies-aged-89 |title=Le Mans winner, Tony Rolt, dies aged 89 |publisher=Autocar |date=8 February 2008 |accessdate=30 December 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"Drunken Tale\">{{cite web|url=http://vennmotorsport.wordpress.com/2013/01/31/the-drunken-tale-of-duncan-hamilton/ |title=The Drunken Tale Of Duncan Hamilton &#124; Venn Motor Sport |publisher=Vennmotorsport.wordpress.com |date=31 January 2013 |accessdate=30 December 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"classicdriver.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.classicdriver.com/en/article/classic-life/duncan-hamilton-gentleman-driver |title=Duncan Hamilton, Gentleman Driver &#124; Classic Driver Magazine |publisher=Classicdriver.com |date=31 August 2014 |accessdate=30 December 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Lucky escapes==\n\nOn one occasion in 1947, he was transporting his MG R-type to the [[Brighton Speed Trials]], when going down a hill near [[Guildford]], he \"saw the splendid honeycomb radiator of a Bugatti in the outside rear-view mirror\", so he moved over and waved it past, but the car hung back. Further down the hill, the Bugatti accelerated and drew level with Hamilton, at which point he saw there was no one in it: \"The awful truth dawned on me \u2013 it was my own car, gathering speed fast.\" Hamilton had forgotten he was towing the Bugatti, and the story ends with a lamppost snapped in two.<ref name=\"classicdriver.com\"/><ref name=\"petergiddings.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.petergiddings.com/Peter_articles/hamilton.html |title=Duncan Hamilton |publisher=Petergiddings.com |date= |accessdate=30 December 2015}}</ref>\n\nA week after the 1953 Le Mans win, Hamilton drove to [[Porto|Oporto]] to prepare for the [[Portuguese Grand Prix]]. Held on the [[Circuito da Boavista]], he was leading into the first corner of the race when he crashed his Jaguar heavily into an [[Transmission tower|electricity pylon]]. The Jaguar cartwheeled, throwing him out of the car and into a tree. He hung there for about a minute, before falling down on the side of the circuit. Barely conscious, he moved his legs just as a Ferrari raced by, nearly taking Hamilton's left boot with it. He was taken to hospital for an emergency operation, though the medical facilities did not extend to [[anaesthetic]]; as the surgeon leant over him, Duncan was mesmerised by the increasing length of cigarette ash, as it hovered above his open chest cavity. The accident cut off the power supply to Oporto for several hours.<ref name=\"independent.co.uk\"/><ref name=\"petergiddings.com\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://vennmotorsport.wordpress.com/2013/01/31/the-drunken-tale-of-duncan-hamilton |title=The Drunken Tale Of Duncan Hamilton &#124; Venn Motor Sport |publisher=Vennmotorsport.wordpress.com |date=31 January 2013 |accessdate=30 December 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"oldbrightonians.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.oldbrightonians.com/notable-obs/sport/duncan-hamilton-s.-1934-36.html |title=Duncan Hamilton (S. 1934-36) &#124; Old Brightonians - The Alumni of Brighton College |publisher=Old Brightonians |date= |accessdate=30 December 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Retirement==\n\nHamilton sustained unpleasant injuries during the 1958 24 Hours of Le Mans, while contesting the lead in his Jaguar D-Type, and then he was shattered by the death of his friend [[Mike Hawthorn]] in early 1959. That tragedy finally prompted him to hang up his racing helmet and gloves in 1959, and concentrated on his garage business in Bagshot. His love and passion for the finest classic motor cars led Hamilton to establish his own company back in 1948. Since then, Duncan Hamilton & Co Limited has become an international recognised for being one of the most respected and well-connected specialists in historic cars.<ref name=\"independent.co.uk\"/><ref name=\"oldracingcars.com\">{{cite web|author=Allen Brown |url=http://www.oldracingcars.com/driver/Duncan_Hamilton |title=Duncan Hamilton \u00ab |publisher=Oldracingcars.com |date= |accessdate=30 December 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.duncanhamilton.com/our-heritage/ |title=Our Heritage |publisher=Duncan Hamilton |date= |accessdate=30 December 2015}}</ref>\n \nHe co-wrote an autobiography called ''Touch Wood!''. Duncan Hamilton died in [[Sherborne]], Dorset. His son Adrian Hamilton, a [[classic car]] dealer, runs his father's garage in another location today. Duncan's grandson [[Archie Hamilton (racing driver)|Archie Hamilton]] is also a racing driver.<ref name=\"oldracingcars.com\"/>\n\nAs [[Francis Curzon, 5th Earl Howe|Earl Howe]] wrote in the original autobiography foreword in 1960, though the drivers of his age were fiercely competitive, there were also \"friends to meet, stories to tell and almost certainly a party to be enjoyed.\". Duncan was certainly larger than life, he wasn\u2019t just one of the most successful drivers of the 1950s, but also the man who trespassed at [[Brooklands]], who spent the war in the Fleet Air Arm accidentally trying to drown American Admirals and who was once stopped for speeding whilst rushing to take part in a TV programme on road safety.<ref name=\"oldbrightonians.com\"/><ref name=Hamilton>Duncan Hamilton, \u201cTouch Wood \u2013 The Autobiography of the 1953 Le Mans Winner\u201d (John Blake Publishing, {{ISBN|978-1782197737}}, 2014)</ref>\n\nHamilton is regarded as the epitome of the old school English competitor. He, and many of his contemporaries such as Hawthorn, Rolt and [[Peter Collins (racing driver)|Peter Collins]], raced mainly for the love of the sport, branding them as gentlemen drivers.<ref name=\"petergiddings.com\"/>\n\n==Racing record==\n\n===Career highlights===\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"font-size: 95%;\"\n|-\n! Sea