|1957]]\n|align=\"left\"| {{Flagicon|GBR}} D. Hamilton\n|align=\"left\"| {{flagicon|USA}} [[Masten Gregory]]\n|align=\"left\"| [[Jaguar D-Type]]\n| S5.0\n| 299\n| 6th\n| 6th\n|-\n! [[1958 24 Hours of Le Mans|1958]]\n|align=\"left\"| {{Flagicon|GBR}} J. Duncan Hamilton\n|align=\"left\"| {{flagicon|GBR}} [[Ivor Bueb]]\n|align=\"left\"| [[Jaguar D-Type]]\n| S3.0\n| 251\n| colspan=2|DNF<br>(Accident)\n|}\n\n===Complete 12 Hours of Sebring results===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center; font-size:90%\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Team\n! Co-Drivers\n! Car\n! Class\n! Laps\n! {{Tooltip|Pos.|Overall Position}}\n! {{Tooltip|Class<br>Pos.|Class Position}}\n|-\n! [[1956 12 Hours of Sebring|1956]]\n|align=\"left\"| {{flagicon|USA}} Jaguar of New York Distributors Inc.\n|align=\"left\"| {{Flagicon|GBR}} [[Ivor Bueb]]\n|align=\"left\"| [[Jaguar D-Type]]\n| S5.0\n| 63\n| colspan=2|DNF<br>(Brakes)\n|}\n\n===Complete 12 Hours of Reims results===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center; font-size:90%\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Team\n! Co-Drivers\n! Car\n! Class\n! Laps\n! {{Tooltip|Pos.|Overall Position}}\n! {{Tooltip|Class<br>Pos.|Class Position}}\n|-\n! [[1954 12 Hours of Reims|1954]]\n|align=\"left\"| {{Flagicon|GBR}} [[Jaguar Cars|Jaguar Cars Ltd.]]\n|align=\"left\"| {{flagicon|GBR}} [[Tony Rolt]]\n|align=\"left\"| [[Jaguar D-Type]]\n| \n| 214\n| style=\"background:#dfdfdf;\"| 2nd\n| style=\"background:#dfdfdf;\"| 2nd\n|-\n! [[1956 12 Hours of Reims|1956]]\n|align=\"left\"| {{Flagicon|GBR}} [[Jaguar Cars]]\n|align=\"left\"| {{flagicon|GBR}} [[Ivor Bueb]]\n|align=\"left\"| [[Jaguar D-Type]]\n| S3.5\n|\n| style=\"background:#ffffbf;\"| '''1st'''\n| style=\"background:#ffffbf;\"| '''1st'''\n|}\n\n===Complete 12 Hours of Pescara results===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center; font-size:90%\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Team\n! Co-Drivers\n! Car\n! Class\n! {{Tooltip|Pos.|Overall Position}}\n! {{Tooltip|Class<br>Pos.|Class Position}}\n|-\n! [[1953 12 Hours of Pescara|1953]]\n|align=\"left\"| {{Flagicon|GBR}} [[Peter Whitehead (racing driver)|Peter Whitehead]]\n|align=\"left\"| {{Flagicon|GBR}} [[Peter Whitehead (racing driver)|Peter Whitehead]]\n|align=\"left\"| [[Jaguar C-Type]]\n|S+2.0\n| colspan=2|DNF<br>(Steering)\n|}\n\n===Complete 12 Hours of Hy\u00e8res results===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center; font-size:90%\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Team\n! Co-Drivers\n! Car\n! Class\n! {{Tooltip|Pos.|Overall Position}}\n! {{Tooltip|Class<br>Pos.|Class Position}}\n|-\n! [[1954 12 Hours of Hy\u00e8res|1954]]\n|align=\"left\"| {{Flagicon|GBR}} [[Peter Whitehead (racing driver)|Peter Whitehead]]\n|align=\"left\"| {{Flagicon|GBR}} [[Peter Whitehead (racing driver)|Peter Whitehead]]\n|align=\"left\"| [[Cooper Car Company|Cooper-Climax T33]]\n|\n| colspan=2|DNS\n|}\n\n==References==\n\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==Further reading==\n\n* Duncan Hamilton. ''Touch Wood - The Autobiography of the 1953 Le Man Winner'' John Blake Publishing. 2014 978-1782197737.\n* Paul Skilleter. ''Jaguar Sports Cars''. G T Foulis & Co Ltd. 1976 {{ISBN|978-0854291663}}.\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-sports}}\n{{succession box|title=[[List of 24 Hours of Le Mans winners|Winner of the 24 Hours of Le Mans]] |before= [[Hermann Lang]]<br>[[Fritz Riess]]|after= [[Jos\u00e9 Froil\u00e1n Gonz\u00e1lez]]<br>[[Maurice Trintignant]]|years= [[1953 24 Hours of Le Mans|1953]] <small>with:</small><br>[[Tony Rolt]]}}\n{{succession box|title=[[Wakefield Trophy]] |before= n/a|after= [[Stirling Moss]]<br>1951|years= 1950}}\n{{succession box|title=[[12 Hours of Reims]] |before= [[Peter Whitehead (racing driver)|Peter Whitehead]]<br>[[Ken Wharton]]<br>1954|after= [[Olivier Gendebien]]<br>[[Paul Fr\u00e8re]]<br>1957|years= 1956}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{24 Hours of Le Mans winners}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hamilton, Duncan}}\n[[Category:English racing drivers]]\n[[Category:English Formula One drivers]]\n[[Category:Talbot Formula One drivers]]\n[[Category:Hersham and Walton Motors Formula One drivers]]\n[[Category:1920 births]]\n[[Category:1994 deaths]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Cork (city)]]\n[[Category:People educated at Brighton College]]\n[[Category:Fleet Air Arm aviators]]\n[[Category:World Sportscar Championship drivers]]\n[[Category:24 Hours of Le Mans drivers]]\n[[Category:24 Hours of Le Mans winning drivers]]\n[[Category:24 Hours of Spa drivers]]\n[[Category:Mille Miglia drivers]]\n[[Category:12 Hours of Reims drivers]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|British racing driver}}\n{{tone|date=February 2020}}\n{{Use British English|date=May 2015}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2012}}\n{{Infobox racing driver\n| name = Duncan Hamilton\n| image =\n| caption =\n| nationality = Irish\n| birth_name = James Duncan Hamilton\n| birth_date = {{birth date|1920|4|30|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Cork (city)|Cork]], [[County Cork]], [[History of Ireland (1801\u20131923)|Ireland]],\n| death_date = {{death date and age|1994|5|13|1920|4|30|df=y}}\n| death_place = [[Sherborne]], [[Dorset]], England, UK\n| record template1 =\n  {{Infobox F1 driver|subbox=yes\n  | Years = {{F1|1951}}\u2013{{F1|1953}}\n  | Team(s) = privateer [[Talbot-Lago]], [[Hersham and Walton Motors|HWM]]\n  | Races = 5\n  | Championships = 0\n  | Wins = 0\n  | Podiums = 0\n  | Points = 0\n  | Poles = 0\n  | Fastest laps = 0\n  | First race = [[1951 British Grand Prix]]\n  | First win = \n  | Last win = \n  | Last race = [[1953 British Grand Prix]]\n  }}\n| record template2 =\n  {{Infobox Le Mans driver|subbox=yes\n  | Years       = {{24hLM|1950}}\u2013{{24hLM|1958}}\n  | Teams       = [[Nash-Healey|Nash-Healey Motors]], [[Jaguar Cars|Jaguar Cars Ltd.]], [[Scuderia Ferrari]], J. Duncan Hamilton\n  | Best Finish = 1st <small>({{24hLM|1953}})\n  | Class Wins  = 1 <small>({{24hLM|1953}})</small>\n  }}\n}}\n\n'''James Duncan Hamilton''' (30 April 1920 in [[Cork (city)|Cork]], [[County Cork]], Ireland \u2013 13 May 1994 in [[Sherborne]], Dorset, England). His colourful and extrovert personality often overshadowed his genuine talent. After fighting in, and surviving the [[Second World War]], he vowed to live life to the full and took up motor sport. Although adept in [[Open-wheel|single-seaters]], sportscars was where he enjoyed most success, winning the [[1953 24 Hours of Le Mans|1953 24 Heures du Mans]], two Coupe de Paris events, and the [[12 Hours of Reims|12 heures internationals Reims]] race in 1956. He retired in 1958 and ran a garage in [[Bagshot]], [[Surrey]] for many years. He died from [[lung cancer]] in 1994.\n\n==Early years==\n\nBorn in County Cork, Hamilton was brought up in relative obscurity. Prior to his 20th birthday, Europe was already embroiled in the [[Second World War]]. As a result, he would spend the war years as part of the [[Fleet Air Arm]] flying [[Westland Lysander|Lysanders]]. After the war ended, he opened a car garage. During the years between the war ending and the start of the 1950s, Duncan started racing in local events. He cut his teeth in such pre-wars as the [[MG R-type]] and the [[Bugatti Type 35]]B. After racing a [[Maserati 6CM]] in 1948, Duncan graduated to a [[Talbot-Lago]] Grand Prix car.<ref name=\"conceptcarz.com\">{{cite web |url=http://www.conceptcarz.com/view/racing/driver.aspx?driverID=40&dtaID=21 |title=Duncan Hamilton - 1951 Formula One Season |last=McMullen |first=Jeremy |publisher=conceptcarz |accessdate=20 January 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Formula One career==\n\nHe participated in five World Championship Grands Prix and 18 non-Championship [[Formula One]] races. His best results in the non-Championship events were fourth place in the 1948 Zandvoort Grand Prix with a [[Maserati 6CM]], third in the 1951 Richmond Trophy ([[English Racing Automobiles|ERA]] B-Type), second in the [[BRDC International Trophy|1951 BRDC International Trophy]] ([[Talbot-Lago]] T26C), third in the 1952 Richmond Trophy (Talbot-Lago T26C) and fourth in the 1952 Internationales ADAC Eifelrennen ([[Hersham and Walton Motors|HWM]]-[[Alta Car and Engineering Company|Alta]]).<ref>{{cite web|author=Darren Galpin |url=http://www.silhouet.com/motorsport/archive/f1/title.html |title=The Formula One Archives |publisher=Silhouet.com |date= |accessdate=30 December 2015}}</ref>\n\nThat fourth place at [[Circuit Park Zandvoort|Zandvoort]], showed that he was right at home in the upper level of Grand Prix racing, especially as this was his debut at this level. After that impressive debut, things soon turned sour for Hamilton, at his last race of 1948, the [[1948 British Grand Prix|RAC International Grand Prix]], the first official post-WW2 British Grand Prix, he retired with oil pressure problems.<ref name=\"conceptcarz.com\"/><ref name=\"f1-images.de\">{{cite web|url=http://www.f1-images.de/009900/nowm/481002.htm |title=f1-images.de |publisher=f1-images.de |date= |accessdate=30 December 2015}}</ref>\n\nThroughout the 1949 Grand Prix season, he only suffered one retirement, however he did not finish higher than ninth, which he managed twice, both times at [[Goodwood Circuit|Goodwood]]. The following season, he competed in fewer Grand Prix races, while he expanded his racing experience by racing sportscars. He won the Wakefield Trophy, a minor [[Formula Libre]] race, held at [[Curragh]] in the Republic of Ireland. Hamilton performed beautifully before the Irish crowd.<ref name=\"conceptcarz.com\"/><ref name=\"f1-images.de\"/>\n\nIn the wet, Hamilton had few peers. In his Talbot-Lago, he eclipsed even [[Juan Manuel Fangio]] at the soaking BRDC International Trophy race at [[Silverstone Circuit|Silverstone]] in 1951, when he finished second to [[Reg Parnell]], but a long way ahead of Fangio who went on to win the World Championship that season.<ref name=\"independent.co.uk\">{{cite news|author=David Tremayne |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/people/obituary-duncan-hamilton-1416114.html |title=Obituary: Duncan Hamilton &#124; People &#124; News |publisher=The Independent |date= |accessdate=30 December 2015}}</ref>\n\n==24 Hours of Le Mans==\n\nHe was best known for his success in the [[24 Hours of Le Mans]] endurance race, which he took part in nine times, most famously in partnership with [[Tony Rolt]]. The pair finished fourth at their first attempt in the [[1950 24 Hours of Le Mans|1950 race]] and sixth in [[1951 24 Hours of Le Mans|1951]], both times in a special-bodied [[Nash-Healey]] coupe. Their [[Jaguar C-Type]] did not finish in [[1952 24 Hours of Le Mans|1952]], but they returned with a C-Type to win in [[1953 24 Hours of Le Mans|1953]]. They were second with a [[Jaguar D-Type]] in [[1954 24 Hours of Le Mans|1954]], losing to a much larger-engined V12 Ferrari \u2013 and by the narrowest margin in years. They came within two miles of victory, Hamilton driving a storming race in the closing stages to halve the lead of the [[Scuderia Ferrari]] of [[Jos\u00e9 Froil\u00e1n Gonz\u00e1lez]] and [[Maurice Trintignant]], as the track was awash following a cloudburst. When the track started to dry out, the Ferrari hung on for a narrow triumph. He failed to finish in [[1955 24 Hours of Le Mans|1955]]. For [[1956 24 Hours of Le Mans|1956]] Hamilton partnered [[Alfonso de Portago]] in a [[Ferrari]] but again did not finish. In [[1957 24 Hours of Le Mans|1957]] he reverted to a Jaguar D-Type: partnered by the American driver [[Masten Gregory]] he came sixth. His last Le Mans appearance was in [[1958 24 Hours of Le Mans|1958]], when the D-Type he shared with [[Ivor Bueb]] failed to finish.<ref name=\"independent.co.uk\"/><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.topgear.com/content/features/stories/2007/04/stories/07/1.html |title=CAMRRAD: Duncan Hamilton |work=topgear.com |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070712042621/http://www.topgear.com/content/features/stories/2007/04/stories/07/1.html |archivedate=12 July 2007 |accessdate=10 January 2016}}</ref>\n\nHamilton also won the 1956 [[Reims-Gueux|Rheims]] 12-hour race for Jaguar with a D-Type co-driven by Ivor Bueb. Despite the win, the factory dropped him from their 1956 Le Mans roster for speeding up and passing team-mate [[Paul Fr\u00e8re]]'s car at Rheims when Lofty England had ordered the entire team to slow down, hence his switch to a Ferrari that year. In 1957 Jaguar did not enter Le Mans&nbsp;\u2013 cars and equipment had been destroyed by a fire at the factory&nbsp;\u2013 and Hamilton used his privately owned D-Type.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mike-hawthorn.org.uk/d-type.php |title=Mike Hawthorn's Tribute Site - the Jaguar D-Type |website=mike-hawthorn.org.uk |accessdate=10 January 2016 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071203093050/http://www.mike-hawthorn.org.uk/d-type.php |archivedate=3 December 2007 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n===Called from the bar===\n\n[[File:1953JaguarC-Type.jpg|thumb|[[Jaguar C-Type]], similar to which Hamilton and Rolt drove to victory at Le Mans]]\nHamilton famously won the [[1953 24 Hours of Le Mans|1953 event]] in a Jaguar C-Type shared with Rolt. Initially, the pairing were disqualified for practising in a Jaguar that had the same racing number as another on the circuit at the same time, but they were reinstated. Hamilton's account has become a motor racing legend: when Jaguar team manager [[Lofty England]] persuaded the organisers to let them race, both drivers were already drunk in a local bar.  England said: \"Of course I would never have let them race under the influence. I had enough trouble when they were sober!\"<ref name=\"Rolt obit\" />\n\nWhen the race was under way the team tried to sober Hamilton up by giving him coffee during the pit stops but he refused it, saying it made his arms twitch; instead he was given brandy. The alcohol must have helped when he struck a bird face first at 130&nbsp;mph and broke his nose. Despite the bizarre circumstances, the duo went on to win the race and recorded the first 100&nbsp;mph average speed at Le Mans, a record pace.<ref name=\"Drunken Tale />\n\nBoth England and Rolt have denied that they were drunk.<ref name=\"Rolt obit\">{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/obituaries/1577975/Tony-Rolt.html |title=Tony Rolt |publisher=Telegraph |date= |accessdate=30 December 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/?view=DETAILS&grid=&xml=/news/2008/02/08/db0801.xml |title=News - Latest breaking UK news |publisher=Telegraph |date= |accessdate=30 December 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=Alan Henry |url=https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2008/feb/09/motorsports.sportobituaries |title=Obituary: Tony Rolt &#124; Sport |publisher=The Guardian |date= |accessdate=30 December 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.autocar.co.uk/car-news/motorsport/le-mans-winner-tony-rolt-dies-aged-89 |title=Le Mans winner, Tony Rolt, dies aged 89 |publisher=Autocar |date=8 February 2008 |accessdate=30 December 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"Drunken Tale>{{cite web|url=http://vennmotorsport.wordpress.com/2013/01/31/the-drunken-tale-of-duncan-hamilton/ |title=The Drunken Tale Of Duncan Hamilton &#124; Venn Motor Sport |publisher=Vennmotorsport.wordpress.com |date=31 January 2013 |accessdate=30 December 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"classicdriver.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.classicdriver.com/en/article/classic-life/duncan-hamilton-gentleman-driver |title=Duncan Hamilton, Gentleman Driver &#124; Classic Driver Magazine |publisher=Classicdriver.com |date=31 August 2014 |accessdate=30 December 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Lucky escapes==\n\nOn one occasion in 1947, he was transporting his MG R-type to the [[Brighton Speed Trials]], when going down a hill near [[Guildford]], he \"saw the splendid honeycomb radiator of a Bugatti in the outside rear-view mirror\", so he moved over and waved it past, but the car hung back. Further down the hill, the Bugatti accelerated and drew level with Hamilton, at which point he saw there was no one in it: \"The awful truth dawned on me \u2013 it was my own car, gathering speed fast.\" Hamilton had forgotten he was towing the Bugatti, and the story ends with a lamppost snapped in two.<ref name=\"classicdriver.com\"/><ref name=\"petergiddings.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.petergiddings.com/Peter_articles/hamilton.html |title=Duncan Hamilton |publisher=Petergiddings.com |date= |accessdate=30 December 2015}}</ref>\n\nA week after the 1953 Le Mans win, Hamilton drove to [[Porto|Oporto]] to prepare for the [[Portuguese Grand Prix]]. Held on the [[Circuito da Boavista]], he was leading into the first corner of the race when he crashed his Jaguar heavily into an [[Transmission tower|electricity pylon]]. The Jaguar cartwheeled, throwing him out of the car and into a tree. He hung there for about a minute, before falling down on the side of the circuit. Barely conscious, he moved his legs just as a Ferrari raced by, nearly taking Hamilton's left boot with it. He was taken to hospital for an emergency operation, though the medical facilities did not extend to [[anaesthetic]]; as the surgeon leant over him, Duncan was mesmerised by the increasing length of cigarette ash, as it hovered above his open chest cavity. The accident cut off the power supply to Oporto for several hours.<ref name=\"independent.co.uk\"/><ref name=\"petergiddings.com\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://vennmotorsport.wordpress.com/2013/01/31/the-drunken-tale-of-duncan-hamilton |title=The Drunken Tale Of Duncan Hamilton &#124; Venn Motor Sport |publisher=Vennmotorsport.wordpress.com |date=31 January 2013 |accessdate=30 December 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"oldbrightonians.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.oldbrightonians.com/notable-obs/sport/duncan-hamilton-s.-1934-36.html |title=Duncan Hamilton (S. 1934-36) &#124; Old Brightonians - The Alumni of Brighton College |publisher=Old Brightonians |date= |accessdate=30 December 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Retirement==\n\nHamilton sustained unpleasant injuries during the 1958 24 Hours of Le Mans, while contesting the lead in his Jaguar D-Type, and then he was shattered by the death of his friend [[Mike Hawthorn]] in early 1959. That tragedy finally prompted him to hang up his racing helmet and gloves in 1959, and concentrated on his garage business in Bagshot. His love and passion for the finest classic motor cars led Hamilton to establish his own company back in 1948. Since then, Duncan Hamilton & Co Limited has become an international recognised for being one of the most respected and well-connected specialists in historic cars.<ref name=\"independent.co.uk\"/><ref name=\"oldracingcars.com\">{{cite web|author=Allen Brown |url=http://www.oldracingcars.com/driver/Duncan_Hamilton |title=Duncan Hamilton \u00ab |publisher=Oldracingcars.com |date= |accessdate=30 December 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.duncanhamilton.com/our-heritage/ |title=Our Heritage |publisher=Duncan Hamilton |date= |accessdate=30 December 2015}}</ref>\n \nHe co-wrote an autobiography called ''Touch Wood!''. Duncan Hamilton died in [[Sherborne]], Dorset. His son Adrian Hamilton, a [[classic car]] dealer, runs his father's garage in another location today. Duncan's grandson [[Archie Hamilton (racing driver)|Archie Hamilton]] is also a racing driver.<ref name=\"oldracingcars.com\"/>\n\nAs [[Francis Curzon, 5th Earl Howe|Earl Howe]] wrote in the original autobiography foreword in 1960, though the drivers of his age were fiercely competitive, there were also \"friends to meet, stories to tell and almost certainly a party to be enjoyed.\". Duncan was certainly larger than life, he wasn\u2019t just one of the most successful drivers of the 1950s, but also the man who trespassed at [[Brooklands]], who spent the war in the Fleet Air Arm accidentally trying to drown American Admirals and who was once stopped for speeding whilst rushing to take part in a TV programme on road safety.<ref name=\"oldbrightonians.com\"/><ref name=Hamilton>Duncan Hamilton, \u201cTouch Wood \u2013 The Autobiography of the 1953 Le Mans Winner\u201d (John Blake Publishing, {{ISBN|978-1782197737}}, 2014)</ref>\n\nHamilton is regarded as the epitome of the old school English competitor. He, and many of his contemporaries such as Hawthorn, Rolt and [[Peter Collins (racing driver)|Peter Collins]], raced mainly for the love of the sport, branding them as gentlemen drivers.<ref name=\"petergiddings.com\"/>\n\n==Racing record==\n\n===Career highlights===\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"font-size: 95%;\"\n|-\n! Season\n! Series\n! Position\n! Team\n! Car\n|-\n| 1950\n| Wakefield Trophy  <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.racingsportscars.com/results/Curragh-1950-09-09-9590.html|title=Wakefield Trophy [Formula Libre Hadicap]|publisher=Racing Sports Cars|accessdate=20 January 2016}}</ref>\n| style=\"background:#ffffbf;\"| '''1st'''\n| \n| [[Maserati 6CM]]\n|-\n| 1951\n| [[BRDC International Trophy]]  <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.chicanef1.com/racetit.pl?year=1951&gp=BRDC%20International%20Trophy&r=1|title=1951 BRDC International Trophy|publisher=ChicaneF1 |accessdate=20 January 2016}}</ref>\n| style=\"background:#dfdfdf;\"| 2nd\n|  Duncan Hamilton\n| [[Talbot-Lago|Talbot-Lago T26C]]\n|-\n| \n| Richmond Trophy  <ref>{{cite web|url=http://chicanef1.com/race.pl?year=1951&gp=Richmond%20Trophy&r=1&type=res |title=1951 Richmond Trophy |publisher=ChicaneF1.com |date= |accessdate=9 January 2016}}</ref>\n| style=\"background:#ffdf9f;\"| 3rd\n| \n| [[English Racing Automobiles|ERA B-Type]]\n|-\n| \n| Wakefield Trophy  <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.racingsportscars.com/results/Curragh-1951-09-08-10355.html|title=Wakefield Trophy [Formula Libre]|publisher=Racing Sports Cars|accessdate=20 January 2016}}</ref>\n| style=\"background:#ffdf9f;\"| 3rd\n| [[Hersham and Walton Motors|HWM]]\n| [[Hersham and Walton Motors|HWM]]\n|-\n| 1952\n| Richmond Trophy  <ref>{{cite web|url=http://chicanef1.com/race.pl?year=1952&gp=Richmind%20Trophy&r=1&type=final|title=1945 Robert Benoist Cup|publisher=ChicaneF1 |accessdate=20 January 2016}}</ref>\n| style=\"background:#ffdf9f;\"| 3rd\n| Duncan Hamilton\n| [[Talbot-Lago|Ta