ver)|Peter Whitehead]]<br>[[Ken Wharton]]<br>1954|after= [[Olivier Gendebien]]<br>[[Paul Fr\u00e8re]]<br>1957|years= 1956}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{24 Hours of Le Mans winners}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hamilton, Duncan}}\n[[Category:English racing drivers]]\n[[Category:English Formula One drivers]]\n[[Category:Talbot Formula One drivers]]\n[[Category:Hersham and Walton Motors Formula One drivers]]\n[[Category:1920 births]]\n[[Category:1994 deaths]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Cork (city)]]\n[[Category:People educated at Brighton College]]\n[[Category:Fleet Air Arm aviators]]\n[[Category:World Sportscar Championship drivers]]\n[[Category:24 Hours of Le Mans drivers]]\n[[Category:24 Hours of Le Mans winning drivers]]\n[[Category:24 Hours of Spa drivers]]\n[[Category:Mille Miglia drivers]]\n[[Category:12 Hours of Reims drivers]]\n", "name_user": "G\u00fcnniX", "label": "safe", "comment": "v2.02 -WP:WCWproject (HTML text style element <small> (small text) double - Unbalanced quotes in ref name or illegal character. - Missing end tag)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Duncan_Hamilton_(racing_driver)"}
{"title_page": "Electoral district of Melbourne", "text_new": "{{About|the Victorian state electorate|the seat of the New South Wales Legislative Council (known as City of Melbourne 1848\u201351)|Electoral district of Town of Melbourne|former electorates of the Victorian Legislative Council|Electoral district of City of Melbourne|and|Melbourne Province|the federal electorate|Division of Melbourne}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2019}}\n{{Infobox Australian electorate \n|name     = Melbourne\n|state    = vic\n|image    = VIC Melbourne District 2014.png\n|caption  = Location of Melbourne (dark green) in Greater Melbourne\n|lifespan  = 1856\u20131859, 1889\u2013present\n|mp       = [[Ellen Sandell]] \n|mp-party = [[Australian Greens Victoria|Greens]]\n|namesake = \n|electors = 50393\n|electors_year = 2018\n|area     = 27\n|class    = Central Metropolitan\n| coordinates        = {{coord|37|50|27.3660|S|144|56|47.2452|E|display=inline,title}}\n| near-nw = [[Electoral district of Essendon|Essendon]]\n| near-n  = [[Electoral district of Brunswick|Brunswick]]\n| near-ne = [[Electoral district of Northcote|Northcote]]\n| near-e  = [[Electoral district of Richmond (Victoria)|Richmond]]\n| near-se = [[Electoral district of Prahran|Prahran]]\n| near-s  = [[Electoral district of Albert Park|Albert Park]]\n| near-sw = [[Electoral district of Williamstown|Williamstown]]\n| near-w  = [[Electoral district of Footscray|Footscray]] \n}}\nThe '''electoral district of Melbourne''' is an electorate of the [[Victorian Legislative Assembly]]. It currently includes the localities of [[Carlton, Victoria|Carlton]], [[Carlton North, Victoria|North Carlton]], [[Melbourne city centre|Melbourne]], [[East Melbourne, Victoria|East Melbourne]], [[West Melbourne, Victoria|West Melbourne]], [[North Melbourne]], [[Parkville, Victoria|Parkville]], Newmarket, [[Kensington, Victoria|Kensington]] and [[Flemington, Victoria|Flemington]], and includes [[Melbourne University]]. The district has been in existence since 1856 (it was abolished in 1859 and reestablished in 1889).\n\n[[File:Melbourne_map_1855.jpeg|thumb|Melbourne, 1855]]\n\nThe electorate was won in [[2014 Victorian state election|2014]] for the first time by [[Australian Greens Victoria|Greens]] candidate [[Ellen Sandell]].\n\n==History==\nMelbourne was one of the inaugural districts of the first Assembly in 1856.<ref name=1855Act>\n{{cite web\n |url=http://foundingdocs.gov.au/resources/transcripts/vic5_doc_1855.pdf\n |title=Victoria Constitution Act 1855\n |accessdate=3 January 2014\n}}\n</ref> Its area was defined by the 1855 Act as: {{cquote|''Commencing at a Point in the [[Yarra River|Yarra Yarra River]] due South from the South-western Angle of Gisborne Street, thence to Gisborne Street, and by the Western Side of that Street to [[Victoria Street, Melbourne|Victoria Parade]], thence by the South Side of Victoria Parade to the Western Side of [[Nicholson Street, Melbourne|Nicholson Street]], thence by the said Western Side of Nicholson Street Northwards to the Boundary Line of the Corporate Limits of Melbourne, thence by the last-mentioned Boundary Line bearing West to the [[Moonee Ponds Creek|Moonee Ponds]], by the said Moonee Ponds downwards to the Site of Main\u2019s Bridge,{{ref label|a|a}} thence by a Line bearing South to the Yarra Yarra River, and on the South by the Yarra Yarra River to the commencing Point.''<ref name=1855Act/>}}\n:{{note label|a|a}} <small>now Flemington Bridge</small>\n\nMelbourne was abolished in 1859, its area was split into the new electoral districts of [[Electoral district of East Melbourne|East Melbourne]] and [[Electoral district of West Melbourne|West Melbourne]], each having two members.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.austlii.edu.au/au/legis/vic/hist_act/aatatedovatitnomotlat1066.pdf |title=An Act to alter the Electoral Districts of Victoria and to increase the number of Members of the Legislative Assembly thereof. |year=1858 |accessdate=9 June 2013}}</ref>\n\nMelbourne was re-created as a single-member electorate by the Electoral Act Amendment Act 1888<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.austlii.edu.au/au/legis/vic/hist_act/teaaa1888234/ |title=The Electoral Act Amendment Act 1888 |accessdate=3 January 2014 |type=pdf }}</ref> which took effect at the 1889 elections.\n\nSince 1908 the seat had been traditional [[Australian Labor Party (Victorian Branch)|Labor]] territory since 1908, but had become increasingly marginal against the [[Australian Greens Victoria|Greens]] since 2002. Senior Labor minister [[Bronwyn Pike]] successfully held the seat against strong Greens challenges at three subsequent elections, defeating future Greens Senator [[Richard Di Natale]] in 2002 and 2006, and prominent lawyer [[Brian Walters]] in 2010. Pike resigned in 2012, and Labor candidate and [[City of Melbourne]] councillor [[Jennifer Kanis]] retained the seat after a [[2012 Melbourne state by-election|closely contested by-election]], which saw her finish second on primary votes to Greens candidate Cathy Oke but win on preferences. Kanis lost the seat to Greens candidate [[Ellen Sandell]] at the [[2014 Victorian state election|2014 election]]. Along with the seat of [[Electoral district of Prahran|Prahran]] it was the first win for the Greens in the [[Victorian Legislative Assembly]].\n\n==Members==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!colspan=20 style=\"border-right:0px;\"; | First incarnation (1856\u20131859, 5 members)<ref>{{cite web |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article49758939 |title=The Victorian Parliament |work=South Australian Register |publisher=Trove |accessdate=18 April 2013}}</ref>\n|-\n! colspan=\"2\"|'''Member 1'''\n! '''Party'''\n! '''Term'''\n! colspan=\"2\"|'''Member 2'''\n! '''Party'''\n! '''Term'''\n! colspan=\"2\"|'''Member 3'''\n! '''Party'''\n! '''Term'''\n! colspan=\"2\"|'''Member 4'''\n! '''Party'''\n! '''Term'''\n! colspan=\"2\"|'''Member 5'''\n! '''Party'''\n! '''Term'''\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\"  {{Australian party style|Other}}|&nbsp;\n| rowspan=\"2\" | [[Archibald Michie]]\n| rowspan=\"2\" | None\n| rowspan=\"2\" | 1856\u20131859\n| rowspan=\"2\"   {{Australian party style|Other}}|&nbsp;\n| rowspan=\"2\" | [[David Moore (Australian politician)|David Moore]]\n| rowspan=\"2\" |  None\n| rowspan=\"2\" | 1856\u20131859\n| rowspan=\"2\" {{Australian party style|Other}}|&nbsp;\n| rowspan=\"2\" | [[John Smith (Victoria politician)|John Smith]]<ref>{{Australian Dictionary of Biography |first=Jill |last=Eastwood |title=Smith, John Thomas (1816\u20131879) |id2=smith-john-thomas-4609 |accessdate=18 April 2013}}</ref>\n| rowspan=\"2\" |  None\n| rowspan=\"2\" |  1856\u20131859\n|  {{Australian party style|Other}}|&nbsp;\n|  [[William Stawell]]\n|  None\n|  1856\u20131857\n|  {{Australian party style|Other}}|&nbsp;\n|  [[John O'Shanassy]]<ref name=Sweetman>{{cite book  \n |title=Constitutional Development of Victoria, 1851-6\n |author=Edward Sweetman\n |year=1920\n |publisher=Whitcombe & Tombs Limited\n |page=[https://archive.org/details/constitutionalde00swee/page/183 183]\n |url=https://archive.org/details/constitutionalde00swee\n |accessdate=18 April 2013\n}}</ref>{{ref|note1|#}}\n|  None\n|  1856\n|-\n|  {{Australian party style|Other}}|&nbsp;\n|  [[James Service]]\n|  None\n|  1857\u20131859\n|  {{Australian party style|Other}}|&nbsp;\n|  [[Henry Langlands]]\n|  None\n|  1857\u20131859\n|}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!colspan=4 style=\"border-right:0px;\"; | Second incarnation (1889\u2013present, 1 member)\n|-\n!colspan=\"2\"|Member!!Party!!Term\n|-\n| {{Australian party style|Other}}|&nbsp;\n| [[Godfrey Carter]]\n| None\n| 1889\u20131900\n|-\n| {{Australian party style|Labor}}|&nbsp;\n| [[Edward Findley]]\n| [[Australian Labor Party (Victorian Branch)|Labour]]\n| 1900\u20131901\n|-\n| {{Australian party style|Other}}|&nbsp;\n| [[James Boyd (Australian politician)|James Boyd]]\n| Ministerialist\n| 1901\u20131908\n|-\n| {{Australian party style|Labor}}|&nbsp;\n| [[Alexander Rogers (Australian politician)|Alexander Rogers]]\n| [[Australian Labor Party (Victorian Branch)|Labor]]\n| 1908\u20131924\n|-\n| {{Australian party style|Labor}}|&nbsp;\n| rowspan=\"2\"|[[Tom Hayes (Australian politician)|Tom Hayes]]\n| [[Australian Labor Party (Victorian Branch)|Labor]]\n| 1924\u20131955\n|-\n| {{Australian party style|Labor (Anti-Communist)}}|&nbsp;\n| [[Australian Labor Party (Anti-Communist)|Labor (Anti-Communist)]]\n| 1955\u20131955\n|-\n| {{Australian party style|Labor}}|&nbsp;\n| [[Arthur Clarey]]\n| [[Australian Labor Party (Victorian Branch)|Labor]]\n| 1955\u20131972\n|-\n| {{Australian party style|Labor}}|&nbsp;\n| [[Barry Jones (Australian politician)|Barry Jones]]\n| [[Australian Labor Party (Victorian Branch)|Labor]]\n| 1972\u20131977\n|-\n| {{Australian party style|Labor}}|&nbsp;\n| [[Keith Remington]]\n| [[Australian Labor Party (Victorian Branch)|Labor]]\n| 1977\u20131988\n|-\n| {{Australian party style|Labor}}|&nbsp;\n| [[Neil Cole (politician)|Neil Cole]]\n| [[Australian Labor Party (Victorian Branch)|Labor]]\n| 1988\u20131999\n|-\n| {{Australian party style|Labor}}|&nbsp;\n| [[Bronwyn Pike]]\n| [[Australian Labor Party (Victorian Branch)|Labor]]\n| 1999\u20132012\n|-\n| {{Australian party style|Labor}}|&nbsp;\n| [[Jennifer Kanis]]\n| [[Australian Labor Party (Victorian Branch)|Labor]]\n| 2012\u20132014\n|-\n| {{Australian party style|Greens}}|&nbsp;\n| [[Ellen Sandell]]\n| [[Australian Greens Victoria|Greens]]\n| 2014\u2013present\n|-\n|}\n\n==Election results==\n{{main|Electoral results for the district of Melbourne}}\n\n{{Election box begin\n|title=[[2018 Victorian state election]]: Melbourne<ref>[https://www.vec.vic.gov.au/Results/State2018/MelbourneDistrict.html State Election 2018: Melbourne District], VEC.</ref>\n}}\n{{Election box candidate AU party\n|candidate = [[Ellen Sandell]]\n|party = Greens VIC\n|votes = 15,755\n|percentage = 38.85\n|change = \u22122.59\n}}\n{{Election box candidate AU party\n|candidate = [[Jennifer Kanis]]\n|party = Labor 